# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: oar
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:oar/abri-de-la-madeleine] The archaeological site **Abri de la Madeleine** (Magdalene Shelter) is a rock shelter under an overhanging cliff situated near Tursac, in the Dordogne *département* of the Aquitaine région of southwestern France.
[src:oar/abri-de-la-madeleine] It represents the type site of the Magdalenian culture of the Upper Paleolithic.
[src:oar/abri-de-la-madeleine] The shelter was also occupied during the Middle Ages.
[src:oar/abri-de-la-madeleine] The medieval castle of Petit Marsac stands on the top of the cliff just above the shelter.
[src:oar/abri-de-la-madeleine] Édouard Lartet, financed and helped by the Englishman Henry Christy, were the first systematic excavators of the site, starting in 1863, and published their findings in 1875 under the name of the Age of the Reindeer ("L'âge du renne").
[src:oar/abri-de-la-madeleine] Objects that were found at the **la Madeleine** site are distributed among a number of museums, including the Muséum de Toulouse, the Musee des Antiquites Nationales, St.
[src:oar/abri-de-la-madeleine] The Abri de la Madeleine is classified as a *Monument historique* since 1956.
[src:oar/abri-de-la-madeleine] In 1979, the Abri de la Madeleine was inscribed on the UNESCO World Heritage List as part of the *Prehistoric Sites and Decorated Caves of the Vézère Valley* because of its unique paleolithic artwork and archeological importance.
[src:oar/acheulean] Acheulean tools were produced during the Lower Palaeolithic era across Africa and much of West Asia, South Asia, East Asia and Europe, and are typically found with *Homo erectus* remains.
[src:oar/acheulean] It is thought that Acheulean technologies first developed about 2 million years ago, derived from the more primitive Oldowan technology associated with *Homo habilis*.
[src:oar/acheulean] The Acheulean includes at least the early part of the Middle Paleolithic.
[src:oar/acheulean] Its end is not well defined; if Sangoan (also known as Epi-Acheulean) is included, it may be taken to last until as late as 130,000 years ago.
[src:oar/acheulean] In Europe and Western Asia, early Neanderthals utilized Acheulean technology, later transitioning to the more advanced Mousterian beginning around 320,000 years ago.
[src:oar/acheulean] The type site for the Acheulean is Saint-Acheul, a suburb of Amiens, the capital of the Somme department in Picardy, where artifacts were found in 1859.
[src:oar/acheulean] John Frere is generally credited as being the first to suggest a very ancient date for Acheulean hand-axes.
[src:oar/acheulean] In 1797, he sent two examples to the Royal Academy in London from Hoxne in Suffolk.
[src:oar/acheulean] He had found them in prehistoric lake deposits along with the bones of extinct animals and concluded that they were made by people "who had not the use of metals" and that they belonged to a "very ancient period indeed, even beyond the present world".
[src:oar/acheulean] His ideas were, however, ignored by his contemporaries, who subscribed to a pre-Darwinian view of human evolution.
[src:oar/acheulean] Later, Jacques Boucher de Crèvecœur de Perthes, working between 1836 and 1846, collected further examples of hand-axes and fossilised animal bone from the gravel river terraces of the Somme near Abbeville in northern France.
[src:oar/acheulean] Again, his theories attributing great antiquity to the finds were spurned by his colleagues, until one of de Perthes' main opponents, Marcel Jérôme Rigollot, began finding more tools near Saint Acheul.
[src:oar/acheulean] Following visits to both Abbeville and Saint Acheul by the geologist Joseph Prestwich, the age of the tools was finally accepted.
[src:oar/acheulean] In 1872, Louis Laurent Gabriel de Mortillet described the characteristic hand-axe tools as belonging to *L'Epoque de St Acheul*.
[src:oar/acheulean] The industry was renamed as the Acheulean in 1925.
[src:oar/acheulean] Providing calendrical dates and ordered chronological sequences in the study of early stone tool manufacture is often accomplished through one or more geological techniques, such as radiometric dating, often potassium-argon dating, and magnetostratigraphy.
[src:oar/acheulean] From the Konso Formation of Ethiopia, Acheulean hand-axes are dated to about 1.5 million years ago using radiometric dating of deposits containing volcanic ashes.
[src:oar/acheulean] Acheulean tools in South Asia have also been found to be dated as far as 1.5 million years ago.
[src:oar/acheulean] However, in 2003 examples of the Acheulean from the West Turkana region of Kenya were described which have been dated through the method of magnetostratigraphy to about 1.76 million years ago, and in 2023 finds from Ethiopia were reported dating to 1.95 million years ago.
[src:oar/acheulean] The earliest user of Acheulean tools may have been *Homo ergaster*, who first appeared about 1.8 million years ago (not all researchers use this formal name, and instead prefer to call these users *early Homo erectus*).
[src:oar/acheulean] However, it is impossible to know for sure whether *Homo ergaster* was the only maker of early Acheulean tools, since other hominin species, such as *Homo habilis*, also lived in East Africa at this time.
[src:oar/acheulean] From geological dating of sedimentary deposits, it appears that the Acheulean originated in Africa and spread to Asian, Middle Eastern, and European areas sometime between 1.5 million years ago and about 800 thousand years ago.
[src:oar/acheulean] In individual regions, this dating can be considerably refined; in Europe for example, it was thought that Acheulean methods did not reach the continent until around 500,000 years ago.
[src:oar/acheulean] However, more recent research demonstrated that hand-axes from Spain were made more than 900,000 years ago.
[src:oar/acheulean] It is therefore important not to see the Acheulean as a neatly defined period or one that happened as part of a clear sequence but as one tool-making technique that flourished especially well in early prehistory.
[src:oar/acheulean] The enormous geographic spread of Acheulean techniques also makes the name unwieldy as it represents numerous regional variations on a similar theme.
[src:oar/acheulean] The term Acheulean does not represent a common culture in the modern sense, rather it is a basic method for making stone tools that was shared across much of the Old World.
[src:oar/acheulean] In Europe, the more advanced Mousterian utilizing the Levallois technique appeared around 320,000 years ago, and had displaced the Acheulean in Europe and the Middle East by around 125,000 years ago.
[src:oar/acheulean] The Acheulean had also disappeared from Africa by this time.
[src:oar/acheulean] The Acheulean may have lasted much later, until around 50,000 years ago in East Asia.
[src:oar/acheulean] The Mode 1 industries created rough flake tools by hitting a suitable stone with a hammerstone.
[src:oar/acheulean] The resulting flake that broke off would have a natural sharp edge for cutting and could afterwards be sharpened further by striking another smaller flake from the edge if necessary (known as "retouch").
[src:oar/acheulean] These early toolmakers may also have worked the stone they took the flake from (known as a core) to create chopper cores although there is some debate over whether these items were tools or just discarded cores.
[src:oar/acheulean] Advanced, later Acheulean toolmakers supplemented stone-on-stone percussion by utilizing "soft hammer" percussion using bone, antler, or wood tools.
[src:oar/acheulean] These type of hammers, compared to stone, yields more control over the shape of the finished tool, and can be used to resharpen blunted tools.
[src:oar/acheulean] The oldest locality showing evidence of "soft hammer" percussion in Eurasia is the Boxgrove site in southern England, dating to around 480,000 years ago.
[src:oar/acheulean] Soft hammer percussion may have emerged around the same time in Africa.
[src:oar/acheulean] Unlike the earlier Mode 1 industries, it was the core that was prized over the flakes that came from it.
[src:oar/acheulean] Another advance was that the Mode 2 tools were worked symmetrically and on both sides indicating greater care in the production of the final tool.
[src:oar/acheulean] Mode 3 technology emerged towards the end of Acheulean dominance and involved the Levallois technique, most famously exploited by the Mousterian industry.
[src:oar/acheulean] Transitional tool forms between the two are called Mousterian of Acheulean Tradition, or MTA types.
[src:oar/acheulean] The long blades of the Upper Palaeolithic Mode 4 industries appeared long after the Acheulean was abandoned.
[src:oar/acheulean] As the period of Acheulean tool use is so vast, efforts have been made to classify various stages of it such as John Wymer's division into Early Acheulean, Middle Acheulean, Late Middle Acheulean and Late Acheulean for material from Britain.
[src:oar/acheulean] These schemes are normally regional and their dating and interpretations vary.
[src:oar/acheulean] In Africa, there is a distinct difference in the tools made before and after 600,000 years ago with the older group being thicker and less symmetric and the younger being more extensively trimmed.
[src:oar/acheulean] The primary innovation associated with Acheulean hand-axes is that the stone was worked symmetrically and on both sides.
[src:oar/acheulean] For the latter reason, handaxes are, along with cleavers, bifacially worked tools that could be manufactured from the large flakes themselves or from prepared cores.
[src:oar/acheulean] Tool types found in Acheulean assemblages include pointed, cordate, ovate, ficron, and bout-coupé hand-axes (referring to the shapes of the final tool), cleavers, retouched flakes, scrapers, and segmental chopping tools.
[src:oar/acheulean] Materials used were determined by available local stone types; flint is most often associated with the tools but its use is concentrated in Western Europe; in Africa sedimentary and igneous rock such as mudstone and basalt were most widely used, for example.
[src:oar/acheulean] Other source materials include chalcedony, quartzite, andesite, sandstone, chert, and shale.
[src:oar/acheulean] Even relatively soft rock such as limestone could be exploited.
[src:oar/acheulean] In all cases the toolmakers worked their handaxes close to the source of their raw materials, suggesting that the Acheulean was a set of skills passed between individual groups.
[src:oar/acheulean] Some smaller tools were made from large flakes that had been struck from stone cores.
[src:oar/acheulean] These flake tools and the distinctive waste flakes produced in Acheulean tool manufacture suggest a more considered technique, one that required the toolmaker to think one or two steps ahead during work that necessitated a clear sequence of steps to create perhaps several tools in one sitting.
[src:oar/acheulean] A hard hammerstone would first be used to rough out the shape of the tool from the stone by removing large flakes.
[src:oar/acheulean] These large flakes might be re-used to create tools.
[src:oar/acheulean] The tool maker would work around the circumference of the remaining stone core, removing smaller flakes alternately from each face.
[src:oar/acheulean] The scar created by the removal of the preceding flake would provide a striking platform for the removal of the next.
[src:oar/acheulean] Misjudged blows or flaws in the material used could cause problems, but a skilled toolmaker could overcome them.
[src:oar/acheulean] Once the roughout shape was created, a further phase of flaking was undertaken to make the tool thinner.
[src:oar/acheulean] The thinning flakes were removed using a softer hammer, such as bone or antler.
[src:oar/acheulean] The softer hammer required more careful preparation of the striking platform and this would be abraded using a coarse stone to ensure the hammer did not slide off when struck.
[src:oar/acheulean] Final shaping was then applied to the usable cutting edge of the tool, again using fine removal of flakes.
[src:oar/acheulean] Some Acheulean tools were sharpened instead by the removal of a tranchet flake.
[src:oar/acheulean] This was struck from the lateral edge of the hand-axe close to the intended cutting area, resulting in the removal of a flake running along (parallel to) the blade of the axe to create a neat and very sharp working edge.
[src:oar/acheulean] This distinctive tranchet flake can be identified amongst flint-knapping debris at Acheulean sites.
[src:oar/acheulean] Loren Eiseley calculated that Acheulean tools have an average useful cutting edge of 20 centimetres (8 inches), making them much more efficient than the 5 centimetres (2 inches) average of Oldowan tools.
[src:oar/acheulean] A wear analysis of handaxes from the 480,000 year old late Acheulean Boxgrove site in England found that they were primarily if not exclusively used for animal butchery, with no evidence for their use in woodworking or digging.
[src:oar/acheulean] Alternative theories include a use for ovate hand-axes as a kind of hunting discus to be hurled at prey.
[src:oar/acheulean] Puzzlingly, there are also examples of sites where hundreds of hand-axes, many impractically large and also apparently unused, have been found in close association together.
[src:oar/acheulean] Sites such as Melka Kunturé in Ethiopia, Olorgesailie in Kenya, Isimila in Tanzania, and Kalambo Falls in Zambia have produced evidence that suggests Acheulean hand-axes might not always have had a functional purpose.
[src:oar/acheulean] Recently, it has been suggested that the Acheulean tool users adopted the handaxe as a social artifact, meaning that it embodied something beyond its function of a butchery or wood cutting tool.
[src:oar/acheulean] Knowing how to create and use these tools would have been a valuable skill and the more elaborate ones suggest that they played a role in their owners' identity and their interactions with others.
[src:oar/acheulean] This would help explain the apparent over-sophistication of some examples which may represent a "historically accrued social significance".
[src:oar/acheulean] One theory goes further and suggests that some special hand-axes were made and displayed by males in search of a mate, using a large, well-made hand-axe to demonstrate that they possessed sufficient strength and skill to pass on to their offspring.
[src:oar/acheulean] Once they had attracted a female at a group gathering, it is suggested that they would discard their axes, perhaps explaining why so many are found together.
[src:oar/acheulean] This popular sexual selection hypothesis is controversial due to the assumptions made about sexual selection among extinct organisms.
[src:oar/acheulean] Stone knapping with limited digital dexterity makes the center of mass the required direction of flake removal.
[src:oar/acheulean] Physics then dictates a circular or oval end pattern, similar to the handaxe, for a leftover core after flake production.
[src:oar/acheulean] This would explain the abundance, wide distribution, proximity to source, consistent shape, and lack of actual use, of these artifacts.
[src:oar/acheulean] showing important sites of the Acheulean industry (clickable map).
[src:oar/acheulean] The geographic distribution of Acheulean tools – and thus the peoples who made them – is often interpreted as being the result of palaeo-climatic and ecological factors, such as glaciation and the desertification of the Sahara Desert.
[src:oar/acheulean] Acheulean stone tools have been found across the continent of Africa, save for the dense rainforest around the Congo River which is not thought to have been colonized by hominids until later.
[src:oar/acheulean] It is thought that from Africa their use spread north and east to Asia: from Anatolia, through the Arabian Peninsula, across modern day Iran and Pakistan, and into India, and beyond.
[src:oar/acheulean] In Europe their users reached the Pannonian Basin and the western Mediterranean regions, modern day France, the Low Countries, western Germany, and southern and central Britain.
[src:oar/acheulean] Areas further north did not see human occupation until much later, due to glaciation.
[src:oar/acheulean] In Athirampakkam at Chennai in Tamil Nadu the Acheulean age started at 1.51 mya and it is also prior than North India and Europe.
[src:oar/acheulean] Until the 1980s, it was thought that the humans who arrived in East Asia abandoned the hand-axe technology of their ancestors and adopted chopper tools instead.
[src:oar/acheulean] An apparent division between Acheulean and non-Acheulean tool industries was identified by Hallam L.
[src:oar/acheulean] Movius, who drew the Movius Line across northern India to show where the traditions seemed to diverge.
[src:oar/acheulean] Later finds of Acheulean tools at Chongokni in South Korea and also in Mongolia and China, however, cast doubt on the reliability of Movius's distinction.
[src:oar/acheulean] Since then, a different division known as the Roe Line has been suggested.
[src:oar/acheulean] This runs across North Africa to Israel and thence to India, separating two different techniques used by Acheulean toolmakers.
[src:oar/acheulean] North and east of the Roe Line, Acheulean hand-axes were made directly from large stone nodules and cores; while, to the south and west, they were made from flakes struck from these nodules.
[src:oar/acheulean] Possible Acheulean-like bifacial technologies have also been discussed in relation to the Arubo 1 site in General Tinio, Nueva Ecija, Philippines, where archaeologists recovered a proto-handaxe and bifacial cleaver made from locally sourced chert.
[src:oar/acheulean] Pawlik noted that the proto-handaxe "would certainly be regarded as typical for the Early Acheulean" if found in regions traditionally associated with Acheulean industries.
[src:oar/acheulean] The assemblage has been cited in broader discussions regarding the diversity of bifacial technologies in Southeast Asia and the limitations of strict interpretations of the Movius Line.
[src:oar/acheulean] Most notably, however, it is *Homo ergaster* (sometimes called early *Homo erectus*), whose assemblages are almost exclusively Acheulean, who used the technique.
[src:oar/acheulean] Later, the related species *Homo heidelbergensis* (the common ancestor of both Neanderthals and *Homo sapiens*) used it extensively.
[src:oar/acheulean] Late Acheulean tools were still used by species derived from *H. erectus*, including *Homo sapiens idaltu* and early Neanderthals.
[src:oar/acheulean] The symmetry of the hand-axes has been used to suggest that Acheulean tool users possessed the ability to use language; the parts of the brain connected with fine control and movement are located in the same region that controls speech.
[src:oar/acheulean] The wider variety of tool types compared to earlier industries and their aesthetically as well as functionally pleasing form could indicate a higher intellectual level in Acheulean tool users than in earlier hominines.
[src:oar/acheulean] Others argue that there is no correlation between spatial abilities in tool making and linguistic behaviour, and that language is not learned or conceived in the same manner as artefact manufacture.
[src:oar/acheulean] Lower Palaeolithic finds made in association with Acheulean hand-axes, such as the Venus of Berekhat Ram, have been used to argue for artistic expression amongst the tool users.
[src:oar/acheulean] The incised elephant tibia from Bilzingsleben in Germany, and ochre finds from Kapthurin in Kenya and Duinefontein in South Africa, are sometimes cited as being some of the earliest examples of an aesthetic sensibility in human history.
[src:oar/acheulean] There are numerous other explanations put forward for the creation of these artefacts; however, evidence of human art did not become commonplace until around 50,000 years ago, after the emergence of modern *Homo sapiens*.
[src:oar/acheulean] The kill site at Boxgrove in England is another famous Acheulean site.
[src:oar/acheulean] Up until the 1970s these kill sites, often at waterholes where animals would gather to drink, were interpreted as being where Acheulean tool users killed game, butchered their carcasses, and then discarded the tools they had used.
[src:oar/acheulean] Since the advent of zooarchaeology, which has placed greater emphasis on studying animal bones from archaeological sites, this view has changed.
[src:oar/acheulean] Many of the animals at these kill sites have been found to have been killed by other predator animals, so it is likely that humans of the period supplemented hunting with scavenging from already dead animals.
[src:oar/acheulean] Excavations at the Bnot Ya'akov Bridge site, located along the Dead Sea rift in the southern Hula Valley of northern Israel, have revealed evidence of human habitation in the area from as early as 750,000 years ago.
[src:oar/acheulean] Archaeologists from the Hebrew University of Jerusalem claim that the site provides evidence of "advanced human behavior" half a million years earlier than has previously been estimated.
[src:oar/acheulean] Their report describes an Acheulean layer at the site in which numerous stone tools, animal bones, and plant remains have been found.
[src:oar/acheulean] Azykh cave located in Azerbaijan is another site where Acheulean tools were found.
[src:oar/acheulean] In 1968, a lower jaw of a new type of hominid was discovered in the fifth layer (so-called Acheulean layer) of the cave.
[src:oar/acheulean] Specialists named this type "Azykhantropus".
[src:oar/acheulean] Only limited artefactual evidence survives of the users of Acheulean tools other than the stone tools themselves.
[src:oar/acheulean] Cave sites were exploited for habitation, but the hunter-gatherers of the Palaeolithic also possibly built shelters such as those identified in connection with Acheulean tools at Grotte du Lazaret and Terra Amata near Nice in France.
[src:oar/acheulean] The presence of the shelters is inferred from large rocks at the sites, which may have been used to weigh down the bottoms of tent-like structures or serve as foundations for huts or windbreaks.
[src:oar/acheulean] These stones may have been naturally deposited.
[src:oar/acheulean] In any case, a flimsy wood or animal skin structure would leave few archaeological traces after so much time.
[src:oar/acheulean] Fire was seemingly being exploited by *Homo ergaster*, and would have been a necessity in colonising colder Eurasia from Africa.
[src:oar/acheulean] Conclusive evidence of mastery over it this early is, however, difficult to find.
[src:oar/adze] An **adze** (/ædz/) or **adz** is an ancient and versatile cutting tool similar to an axe but with the cutting edge perpendicular to the handle rather than parallel.
[src:oar/adze] Adzes have been used since the Stone Age.
[src:oar/adze] They are used for smoothing or carving wood in hand woodworking, and as a hoe for agriculture and horticulture.
[src:oar/adze] Two basic forms of an adze are the hand adze (short hoe)—a short-handled tool swung with one hand—and the foot adze (hoe)—a long-handled tool capable of powerful swings using both hands, the cutting edge usually striking at foot or shin level.
[src:oar/adze] A similar tool is called a mattock, which differs by having two blades, one perpendicular to the handle and one parallel.
[src:oar/adze] The adze is depicted in ancient Egyptian art from the Old Kingdom onward.
[src:oar/adze] Originally the adze blades were made of stone, but already in the Predynastic Period copper adzes had all but replaced those made of flint.
[src:oar/adze] Stone blades were fastened to the handle by tying and early bronze blades continued this simple construction.
[src:oar/adze] It was not until the later Bronze Age that the handle passes through an eye at the top of the blade.
[src:oar/adze] Examples of Egyptian adzes can be found in museums and on the Petrie Museum website.
[src:oar/adze] The *ahnetjer* (Manuel de Codage transliteration: *aH-nTr*) depicted as an adze-like instrument, was used in the Opening of the Mouth ceremony, intended to convey power over their senses to statues and mummies.
[src:oar/adze] It was apparently the foreleg of a freshly sacrificed bull or cow with which the mouth was touched.
[src:oar/adze] As Iron Age technology moved south into Africa with migrating ancient Egyptians, they carried their technology with them, including adzes.
[src:oar/adze] To this day, iron adzes are used all over rural Africa for various purposes—from digging pit latrines, and chopping firewood, to tilling crop fields—whether they are of maize (corn), coffee, tea, pyrethrum, beans, millet, yams, or a plethora of other cash and subsistence crops.
[src:oar/adze] Prehistoric Māori adzes from New Zealand were for wood carving, typically made from pounamu sourced from the South Island.
[src:oar/adze] During the Māori Archaic period found on the North Island were commonly made from greywacke from Motutapu Island or basalt from Opito Bay in the Coromandel, similar to adzes constructed on other Pacific Islands.
[src:oar/adze] Early period notched adzes found in Northland were primarily made of argillite quarried from locations around the Marlborough and Nelson regions.
[src:oar/adze] At the same time on Henderson Island, a small coral island in eastern Polynesia lacking any rock other than limestone, native populations may have fashioned giant clamshells into adzes.
[src:oar/adze] American Northwest coast native peoples traditionally used adzes for both functional construction (from bowls to canoes) and art (from masks to totem poles).
[src:oar/adze] Northwest coast adzes take two forms: hafted and D-handle.
[src:oar/adze] The hafted form is similar in form to a European adze with the haft constructed from a natural crooked branch which approximately forms a 60% angle.
[src:oar/adze] The thin end is used as the handle and the thick end is flattened and notched such that an adze iron can be lashed to it.
[src:oar/adze] Modern hafts are sometimes constructed from a sawed blank with a dowel added for strength at the crook.
[src:oar/adze] The second form is the D-handle adze which is basically an adze iron with a directly attached handle.
[src:oar/adze] The D-handle, therefore, provides no mechanical leverage.
[src:oar/adze] Northwest coast adzes are often classified by size and iron shape vs. role.
[src:oar/adze] As with European adzes, iron shapes include straight, gutter and lipped.
[src:oar/adze] Where larger Northwest adzes are similar in size to their European counterparts, the smaller sizes are typically much lighter such that they can be used for the detailed smoothing, shaping and surface texturing required for figure carving.
[src:oar/adze] Final surfacing is sometimes performed with a crooked knife.
[src:oar/adze] Ground stone adzes used to be produced by a variety of people in Western New Guinea (Indonesia), Papua New Guinea and some of the smaller Islands of Melanesia and Micronesia.
[src:oar/adze] The hardstone would have been ground on a riverine rock with the help of water until the desired shape was obtained.
[src:oar/adze] It was then fixed to a natural grown angled wood with resin and plant fibers.
[src:oar/adze] Imported steel axes or machetes have now entirely replaced these tools for decades in even the remotest parts of New Guinea.
[src:oar/adze] Indeed, even before the first foreign missionaries or colonial officials arrived in the New Guinea Highlands, inhabitants had already obtained steel tools through trade with their neighbors.
[src:oar/adze] Stone tools are sometimes manufactured to be sold as curios to tourists.
[src:oar/adze] Modern adzes are made from steel with wooden handles, and enjoy limited use: occasionally in semi-industrial areas, but particularly by "revivalists" such as those at the Colonial Williamsburg cultural center in Virginia, United States.
[src:oar/adze] However, the traditional adze has largely been replaced by the sawmill and the powered plane, at least in industrialised cultures.
[src:oar/adze] It remains in use for some specialist crafts, for example by coopers.
[src:oar/adze] Adzes are also in current use by artists such as Northwest Coast American and Canadian Indigenous sculptors doing totem pole carving, as well as masks and bowls.
[src:oar/adze] "Adzes are used for removing heavy waste, leveling, shaping, or trimming the surfaces of timber" and boards.
[src:oar/adze] Generally, the user stands astride a board or log and swings the adze downwards between his feet, chipping off pieces of wood, moving backwards as they go and leaving a relatively smooth surface behind.
[src:oar/adze] Foot adzes are most commonly known as shipbuilder's or carpenter's adzes.
[src:oar/adze] On the modern, steel adze the cutting edge may be flat for smoothing work to very rounded for hollowing work such as bowls, gutters and canoes.
[src:oar/adze] The shoulders or sides of an adze may be curved called a *lipped adze*, used for notching.
[src:oar/adze] The end away from the cutting edge is called the pole and be of different shapes, generally flat or a *pin pole*.
[src:oar/adze] There are a number of specialist, short-handled adzes used by coopers, wainwrights, and chair makers, and in bowl and trough making.
[src:oar/adze] Many of these have shorter handles for control and more curve in the head to allow better clearance for shorter cuts.
[src:oar/adze] During the communist period of Bulgaria, a new multi-use woodworking adze, called Теслà (*Teslà*), emerged.
[src:oar/adze] It has a sharpened edge perpendicular to the handle, resembling an adze, but it is also used like a carpenter's hammer.
[src:oar/adze] On the back of the head is a textured poll for driving nails, and on the front is a V-shaped hole used for prying, to extract the bent nails.
[src:oar/adze] There is a popular Bulgarian folk song called "На теслата дръжката" (eng: The tesla's handle) about a craftsman and the masculinity of his tool.
[src:oar/alligator-drum] The **alligator drum** (simplified Chinese: 鼍鼓; traditional Chinese: 鼉鼓; pinyin: *tuó gǔ*) is a type of drum once used in Neolithic China, made from clay and alligator hides.
[src:oar/alligator-drum] Alligator drums have been found over a broad area at the Neolithic sites from modern Shandong in the east to Qinghai in the west, dating to a period of 5500–2350 BC.
[src:oar/alligator-drum] In literary records, drums manifested shamanistic characteristics and were often used in ritual ceremonies.
[src:oar/alligator-drum] Drums covered with alligator skin for ceremonial use are mentioned in the *Shijing*.
[src:oar/alligator-drum] During the Archaic period, alligators probably lived along the east coast of China, including southern Shandong.
[src:oar/alligator-drum] The earliest alligator drums, comprising a wooden frame covered with alligator skin, are found in the archaeological sites at Dawenkou, as well as several sites of Longshan.
[src:oar/alligator-drum] Typical acoustic characteristics of the alligator drum are as follows: frequency: 4100–2600 Hz, amplitude: 3000–2000 dB, and wavelength: 2300–1900 Hz.
[src:oar/amber] There are five classes of amber, defined on the basis of their chemical constituents.
[src:oar/amber] Because it originates as a soft, sticky tree resin, amber sometimes contains animal and plant material as inclusions.
[src:oar/amber] Amber occurring in coal seams is also called **resinite**, and the term *ambrite* is applied to that found specifically within New Zealand coal seams.
[src:oar/amber] The English word *amber* derives from Arabic *ʿanbar* عنبر from Middle Persian 𐭠𐭭𐭡𐭫 (*ʾnbl* /ambar⁠/, "ambergris") via Middle Latin *ambar* and Middle French *ambre*.
[src:oar/amber] The word referred to what is now known as ambergris (*ambre gris* or "gray amber"), a solid waxy substance derived from the sperm whale.
[src:oar/amber] The word, in its sense of "ambergris", was adopted in Middle English in the 14th century.
[src:oar/amber] In the Romance languages, the sense of the word was extended to Baltic amber (fossil resin) from as early as the late 13th century.
[src:oar/amber] At first called white or yellow amber (*ambre jaune*), this meaning was adopted in English by the early 15th century.
[src:oar/amber] As the use of ambergris waned, this became the main sense of the word.
[src:oar/amber] The two substances ("yellow amber" and "gray amber") conceivably became associated or confused because they both were found washed up on beaches.
[src:oar/amber] Ambergris is less dense than water and floats, whereas amber is denser and floats only in concentrated saline, or strong salty seawater though less dense than stone.
[src:oar/amber] The classical names for amber, Ancient Greek ἤλεκτρον (*ēlektron*) and one of its Latin names, *electrum*, are connected to a term ἠλέκτωρ (*ēlektōr*) meaning "beaming Sun".
[src:oar/amber] According to myth, when Phaëton, son of Helios (the Sun), was killed his mourning sisters became poplar trees, and their tears became *elektron*, amber.
[src:oar/amber] The word *elektron* gave rise to the words *electric, electricity*, and their relatives because of amber's ability to bear a charge of static electricity.
[src:oar/amber] This property is due to its effectiveness as an electrical insulator, which does not allow electron motion from the surface through the substance.
[src:oar/amber] A number of regional and varietal names have been applied to ambers over the centuries, including **allingite**, **beckerite**, **gedanite**, **kochenite**, **krantzite**, and **stantienite**.
[src:oar/amber] Theophrastus discussed amber in the 4th century BCE, as did Pytheas (c.
[src:oar/amber] Earlier Pliny says that Pytheas refers to a large island—three days' sail from the Scythian coast and called Balcia by Xenophon of Lampsacus (author of a fanciful travel book in Greek)—as *Basilia*—a name generally equated with *Abalus*.
[src:oar/amber] Given the presence of amber, the island could have been Heligoland, Zealand, the shores of Gdańsk Bay, the Sambia Peninsula or the Curonian Lagoon, which were historically the richest sources of amber in northern Europe.
[src:oar/amber] There were well-established trade routes for amber connecting the Baltic with the Mediterranean (known as the "Amber Road").
[src:oar/amber] Pliny states explicitly that the Germans exported amber to Pannonia, from where the Veneti distributed it onwards.
[src:oar/amber] The ancient Italic peoples of southern Italy used to work amber; the National Archaeological Museum of Siritide (Museo Archeologico Nazionale della Siritide) at Policoro in the province of Matera (Basilicata) displays important surviving examples.
[src:oar/amber] It has been suggested that amber used in antiquity, as at Mycenae and in the prehistory of the Mediterranean, came from deposits in Sicily.
[src:oar/amber] Pliny also cites the opinion of Nicias (c.
[src:oar/amber] Besides the fanciful explanations according to which amber is "produced by the Sun", Pliny cites opinions that are well aware of its origin in tree resin, citing the native Latin name of *succinum* (*sūcinum*, from *sucus* "juice").
[src:oar/amber] The Romans traded for amber from the shores of the southern Baltic at least as far back as the time of Nero.
[src:oar/amber] Amber has a long history of use in China, with the first written record from 200 BCE.
[src:oar/amber] Early in the 19th century, the first reports of amber found in North America came from discoveries in New Jersey along Crosswicks Creek near Trenton, at Camden, and near Woodbury.
[src:oar/amber] Amber is heterogeneous in composition, consisting of several resinous substances that are more or less soluble in alcohol, ether, and chloroform, along with an insoluble bituminous fraction.
[src:oar/amber] It is a macromolecule formed by free radical polymerization of terpenoid precursors—diterpenes in gymnosperms, particularly labdane-type compounds such as communic acid, communol, and biformene.
[src:oar/amber] In angiosperms, the terpenoids are dominated by triterpenes, although amber from the family Fabaceae also contains labdane-based diterpenes.
[src:oar/amber] These compounds provide alkene groups that enable polymerization.
[src:oar/amber] Over time, amber matures through further polymerization, isomerization, crosslinking, and cyclization, resulting in its characteristic stable, fossilized structure.
[src:oar/amber] Most amber has a hardness between 2.0 and 2.5 on the Mohs scale, a refractive index of 1.5–1.6, a specific gravity between 1.06 and 1.10, and a melting point of 250–300 °C.
[src:oar/amber] Heated above 200 °C (392 °F), amber decomposes, yielding an **oil of amber**, and leaves a black residue which is known as "amber colophony", or "amber pitch"; when dissolved in oil of turpentine or in linseed oil this forms "amber varnish" or "amber lac".
[src:oar/amber] Impurities are quite often present, especially when the resin has dropped onto the ground, so the material may be useless except for varnish-making.
[src:oar/amber] Such inclusion of other substances can cause the amber to have an unexpected color.
[src:oar/amber] *Bony amber* owes its cloudy opacity to numerous tiny bubbles inside the resin.
[src:oar/amber] However, so-called *black amber* is really a kind of jet.
[src:oar/amber] In darkly clouded and even opaque amber, inclusions can be imaged using high-energy, high-contrast, high-resolution X-rays.
[src:oar/amber] Molecular polymerization, resulting from high pressures and temperatures produced by overlying sediment, transforms the resin first into copal.
[src:oar/amber] Sustained heat and pressure drives off terpenes and results in the formation of amber.
[src:oar/amber] For this to happen, the resin must be resistant to decay.
[src:oar/amber] Many trees produce resin, but in the majority of cases this deposit is broken down by physical and biological processes.
[src:oar/amber] Exposure to sunlight, rain, microorganisms, and extreme temperatures tends to disintegrate the resin.
[src:oar/amber] For the resin to survive long enough to become amber, it must be resistant to such forces or be produced under conditions that exclude them.
[src:oar/amber] Fossil resins from Europe fall into two categories, the Baltic ambers and another that resembles the *Agathis* group.
[src:oar/amber] Fossil resins from the Americas and Africa are closely related to the modern genus *Hymenaea*, while Baltic ambers are thought to be fossil resins from plants of the family Sciadopityaceae that once lived in north Europe.
[src:oar/amber] The abnormal development of resin in living trees (*succinosis*) can result in the formation of amber.
[src:oar/amber] Amber is globally distributed in or around all continents, mainly in rocks of Cretaceous age or younger.
[src:oar/amber] Historically, the coast west of Königsberg in Prussia was the world's leading source of amber.
[src:oar/amber] The first mentions of amber deposits there date back to the 12th century.
[src:oar/amber] Juodkrantė in Lithuania was established in the mid-19th century as a mining town of amber.
[src:oar/amber] About 90% of the world's extractable amber is still located in that area, which was transferred to the Russian Soviet Federative Socialist Republic of the USSR in 1946, becoming the Kaliningrad Oblast.
[src:oar/amber] Pieces of amber torn from the seafloor are cast up by the waves and collected by hand, dredging, or diving.
[src:oar/amber] Elsewhere, amber is mined, both in open works and underground galleries.
[src:oar/amber] Then nodules of *blue earth* have to be removed and an opaque crust must be cleaned off, which can be done in revolving barrels containing sand and water.
[src:oar/amber] Erosion removes this crust from sea-worn amber.
[src:oar/amber] Dominican amber is mined through bell pitting, which is dangerous because of the risk of tunnel collapse.
[src:oar/amber] An important source of amber is Kachin State in northern Myanmar, which has been a major source of amber in China for at least 1,800 years.
[src:oar/amber] Contemporary mining of this deposit has attracted attention for unsafe working conditions and its role in funding internal conflict in the country.
[src:oar/amber] Amber from the Rivne Oblast of Ukraine, referred to as Rivne amber, is mined illegally by organised crime groups, who deforest the surrounding areas and pump water into the sediments to extract the amber, causing severe environmental deterioration.
[src:oar/amber] The Vienna amber factories, which use pale amber to manufacture pipes and other smoking tools, turn it on a lathe and polish it with whitening and water or with rotten stone and oil.
[src:oar/amber] The final luster is given by polishing with flannel.
[src:oar/amber] When gradually heated in an oil bath, amber "becomes soft and flexible.
[src:oar/amber] Two pieces of amber may be united by smearing the surfaces with linseed oil, heating them, and then pressing them together while hot.
[src:oar/amber] Cloudy amber may be clarified in an oil bath, as the oil fills the numerous pores that cause the turbidity.
[src:oar/amber] Small fragments, formerly thrown away or used only for varnish are now used on a large scale in the formation of "ambroid" or "pressed amber".
[src:oar/amber] The pieces are carefully heated with exclusion of air and then compressed into a uniform mass by intense hydraulic pressure, the softened amber being forced through holes in a metal plate.
[src:oar/amber] The product is extensively used for the production of cheap jewelry and articles for smoking.
[src:oar/amber] Amber has often been imitated by other resins like copal and kauri gum, as well as by celluloid and even glass.
[src:oar/amber] Baltic amber is sometimes colored artificially but also called "true amber".
[src:oar/amber] Amber occurs in a range of different colors.
[src:oar/amber] As well as the usual yellow-orange-brown that is associated with the color "amber", amber can range from a whitish color through a pale lemon yellow, to brown and almost black.
[src:oar/amber] Other uncommon colors include red amber (sometimes known as "cherry amber"), green amber, and even blue amber, which is rare and highly sought after.
[src:oar/amber] Yellow amber is a hard fossil resin from evergreen trees, and despite the name it can be translucent, yellow, orange, or brown colored.
[src:oar/amber] Found along the southern shore of the Baltic Sea, yellow amber reached the Middle East and western Europe via trade.
[src:oar/amber] Its coastal acquisition may have been one reason yellow amber came to be designated by the same term as ambergris.
[src:oar/amber] Moreover, like ambergris, the resin could be burned as an incense.
[src:oar/amber] The resin's most popular use was, however, for ornamentation—easily cut and polished, it could be transformed into beautiful jewelry.
[src:oar/amber] Much of the most highly prized amber is transparent, in contrast to the very common cloudy amber and opaque amber.
[src:oar/amber] Opaque amber contains numerous minute bubbles.
[src:oar/amber] This kind of amber is known as "bony amber".
[src:oar/amber] Although all Dominican amber is fluorescent, the rarest Dominican amber is blue amber.
[src:oar/amber] It turns blue in natural sunlight and any other partially or wholly ultraviolet light source.
[src:oar/amber] In long-wave UV light it has a very strong reflection, almost white.
[src:oar/amber] Only about 100 kg (220 lb) is found per year, which makes it valuable and expensive.
[src:oar/amber] Sometimes amber retains the form of drops and stalactites, just as it exuded from the ducts and receptacles of the injured trees.
[src:oar/amber] It is thought that, in addition to exuding onto the surface of the tree, amber resin also originally flowed into hollow cavities or cracks within trees, thereby leading to the development of large lumps of amber of irregular form.
[src:oar/amber] Amber can be classified into several forms.
[src:oar/amber] Most fundamentally, there are two types of plant resin with the potential for fossilization.
[src:oar/amber] Terpenoids, produced by conifers and angiosperms, consist of ring structures formed of isoprene (C5H8) units.
[src:oar/amber] Phenolic resins are today only produced by angiosperms, and tend to serve functional uses.
[src:oar/amber] The extinct medullosans produced a third type of resin, which is often found as amber within their veins.
[src:oar/amber] The composition of resins is highly variable; each species produces a unique blend of chemicals which can be identified by the use of pyrolysis–gas chromatography–mass spectrometry.
[src:oar/amber] The overall chemical and structural composition is used to divide ambers into five classes.
[src:oar/amber] There is also a separate classification of amber gemstones, according to the way of production.
[src:oar/amber] It comprises labdatriene carboxylic acids such as communic or ozic acids.
[src:oar/amber] It is further split into three sub-classes.
[src:oar/amber] Classes Ia and Ib utilize regular labdanoid diterpenes (e.g. communic acid, communol, biformenes), while Ic uses *enantio* labdanoids (ozic acid, ozol, *enantio* biformenes).
[src:oar/amber] These ambers are formed from resins with a sesquiterpenoid base, such as cadinene.
[src:oar/amber] Class IV is something of a catch-all: its ambers are not polymerized, but mainly consist of cedrene-based sesquiterpenoids.
[src:oar/amber] Class V resins are considered to be produced by a pine or pine relative.
[src:oar/amber] They comprise a mixture of diterpinoid resins and *n*-alkyl compounds.
[src:oar/amber] Their main variety is *Highgate copalite*.
[src:oar/amber] The oldest amber recovered dates to the late Carboniferous period (320 million years ago).
[src:oar/amber] Amber becomes abundant long after the Carboniferous, in the Early Cretaceous, when it is found in association with insects.
[src:oar/amber] The oldest amber with arthropod inclusions comes from the Late Triassic (late Carnian c.
[src:oar/amber] 230 Ma) of Italy, where four microscopic (0.2–0.1 mm) mites, *Triasacarus,* *Ampezzoa, Minyacarus* and *Cheirolepidoptus,* and a poorly preserved nematoceran fly were found in millimetre-sized droplets of amber.
[src:oar/amber] The oldest amber with significant numbers of arthropod inclusions comes from Lebanon.
[src:oar/amber] This amber, referred to as Lebanese amber, is roughly 125–135 million years old, is considered of high scientific value, providing evidence of some of the oldest sampled ecosystems.
[src:oar/amber] In Lebanon, more than 450 outcrops of Lower Cretaceous amber were discovered by Dany Azar, a Lebanese paleontologist and entomologist.
[src:oar/amber] Among these outcrops, 20 have yielded biological inclusions comprising the oldest representatives of several recent families of terrestrial arthropods.
[src:oar/amber] Even older Jurassic amber has been found recently in Lebanon as well.
[src:oar/amber] Many remarkable insects and spiders were recently discovered in the amber of Jordan including the oldest zorapterans, clerid beetles, umenocoleid roaches, and achiliid planthoppers.
[src:oar/amber] Burmese amber from the Hukawng Valley in northern Myanmar is the only commercially exploited Cretaceous amber.
[src:oar/amber] Uranium–lead dating of zircon crystals associated with the deposit have given an estimated depositional age of approximately 99 million years ago.
[src:oar/amber] Over 1,300 species have been described from the amber, with over 300 in 2019 alone.
[src:oar/amber] Baltic amber is found as irregular nodules in marine glauconitic sand, known as *blue earth*, occurring in Upper Eocene strata of Sambia in Prussia.
[src:oar/amber] It appears to have been partly derived from older Eocene deposits and it occurs also as a derivative phase in later formations, such as glacial drift.
[src:oar/amber] Relics of an abundant flora occur as inclusions trapped within the amber while the resin was yet fresh, suggesting relations with the flora of eastern Asia and the southern part of North America.
[src:oar/amber] Heinrich Göppert named the common amber-yielding pine of the Baltic forests *Pinites succiniter*, but as the wood does not seem to differ from that of the existing genus it has been also called *Pinus succinifera*.
[src:oar/amber] It is improbable that the production of amber was limited to a single species; and indeed a large number of conifers belonging to different genera are represented in the amber-flora.
[src:oar/amber] Amber sometimes contains animals or plant matter that became caught in the resin as it was secreted.
[src:oar/amber] Insects, spiders and even their webs, annelids, frogs, crustaceans, bacteria and amoebae, marine microfossils, wood, flowers and fruit, hair, feathers and other small organisms have been recovered in Cretaceous ambers (deposited c.
[src:oar/amber] An ammonite *Puzosia (Bhimaites)* and marine gastropods have been found in Burmese amber.
[src:oar/amber] The preservation of prehistoric organisms in amber forms a key plot point in Michael Crichton's 1990 novel *Jurassic Park* and the 1993 movie adaptation by Steven Spielberg.
[src:oar/amber] In the story, scientists are able to extract the preserved blood of dinosaurs from prehistoric mosquitoes trapped in amber, from which they genetically clone living dinosaurs.
[src:oar/amber] Scientifically this is as yet impossible, since no amber with fossilized mosquitoes has ever yielded preserved blood.
[src:oar/amber] Amber is, however, conducive to preserving DNA, since it dehydrates and thus stabilizes organisms trapped inside.
[src:oar/amber] One projection in 1999 estimated that DNA trapped in amber could last up to 100 million years, far beyond most estimates of around 1 million years in the most ideal conditions, although a later 2013 study was unable to extract DNA from insects trapped in much more recent Holocene copal.
[src:oar/amber] Amber has been used since prehistory (Solutrean) in the manufacture of jewelry and ornaments, and also in folk medicine.
[src:oar/amber] Amber has been used as jewelry since the Stone Age, from 13,000 years ago.
[src:oar/amber] Amber ornaments have been found in Mycenaean tombs and elsewhere across Europe.
[src:oar/amber] To this day it is used in the manufacture of smoking and glassblowing mouthpieces.
[src:oar/amber] Amber's place in culture and tradition lends it a tourism value; Palanga Amber Museum is dedicated to the fossilized resin.
[src:oar/amber] Amber has long been used in folk medicine for its purported healing properties.
[src:oar/amber] Amber and extracts were used from the time of Hippocrates in ancient Greece for a wide variety of treatments through the Middle Ages and up until the early twentieth century.
[src:oar/amber] Amber necklaces are a traditional European remedy for colic or teething pain with purported analgesic properties of succinic acid, although there is no evidence that this is an effective remedy or delivery method.
[src:oar/amber] The American Academy of Pediatrics and the FDA have warned strongly against their use, as they present both a choking and a strangulation hazard.
[src:oar/amber] In ancient China, it was customary to burn amber during large festivities.
[src:oar/amber] If amber is heated under the right conditions, oil of amber is produced, and in past times this was combined carefully with nitric acid to create "artificial musk" – a resin with a peculiar musky odor.
[src:oar/amber] Although when burned, amber does give off a characteristic "pinewood" fragrance, modern products, such as perfume, do not normally use actual amber because fossilized amber produces very little scent.
[src:oar/amber] In perfumery, scents referred to as "amber" are often created and patented to emulate the opulent golden warmth of the fossil.
[src:oar/amber] The scent of amber was originally derived from emulating the scent of ambergris and/or the plant resin labdanum, but since sperm whales are endangered, the scent of amber is now largely derived from labdanum.
[src:oar/amber] The term "amber" is loosely used to describe a scent that is warm, musky, rich and honey-like, and also somewhat earthy.
[src:oar/amber] Vanilla and cloves are sometimes used to enhance the aroma.
[src:oar/amber] "Amber" perfumes may be created using combinations of labdanum, benzoin resin, copal (a type of tree resin used in incense manufacture), vanilla, Dammara resin and/or synthetic materials.
[src:oar/amber] In Arab Muslim tradition, popular scents include amber, jasmine, musk and oud (agarwood).
[src:oar/amber] Goethe is documented as a rare user of amber, from which he cut lenses to visualize certain optical phenomena.
[src:oar/amber] Motivated by a manuscript sent to him by T.
[src:oar/amber] Seebeck in 1813 "on the reflection and refraction of light", he also conducted experiments on entoptic phenomena.
[src:oar/amber] Goethe attempted to replicate such phenomena on pieces of amber that he pierced himself.
[src:oar/amber] New evidence in 2026 showed that he held a small collection of 42 amber pieces.
[src:oar/amber] Of these, 40 were the subject of a detailed examination for bioinclusions in 2026, during which two nematoceran flies and an ant were found.
[src:oar/archaeoastronomy-p01] Archaeoastronomy uses a variety of methods to uncover evidence of past practices including archaeology, anthropology, astronomy, statistics and probability, and history.
[src:oar/archaeoastronomy-p01] Because these methods are diverse and use data from such different sources, integrating them into a coherent argument has been a long-term difficulty for archaeoastronomers.
[src:oar/archaeoastronomy-p01] Archaeoastronomy fills complementary niches in landscape archaeology and cognitive archaeology.
[src:oar/archaeoastronomy-p01] Material evidence and its connection to the sky can reveal how a wider landscape can be integrated into beliefs about the cycles of nature, such as Mayan astronomy and its relationship with agriculture.
[src:oar/archaeoastronomy-p01] Other examples which have brought together ideas of cognition and landscape include studies of the cosmic order embedded in the roads of settlements.
[src:oar/archaeoastronomy-p01] Archaeoastronomy can be applied to all cultures and all time periods.
[src:oar/archaeoastronomy-p01] The meanings of the sky vary from culture to culture; nevertheless there are scientific methods which can be applied across cultures when examining ancient beliefs.
[src:oar/archaeoastronomy-p01] It is perhaps the need to balance the social and scientific aspects of archaeoastronomy which led Clive Ruggles to describe it as "a field with academic work of high quality at one end but uncontrolled speculation bordering on lunacy at the other".
[src:oar/archaeoastronomy-p01] Two hundred years before John Michell wrote the above, there were no archaeoastronomers and there were no professional archaeologists, but there were astronomers and antiquarians.
[src:oar/archaeoastronomy-p01] Late in the nineteenth century astronomers such as Richard Proctor and Charles Piazzi Smyth investigated the astronomical orientations of the pyramids.
[src:oar/archaeoastronomy-p01] The term *archaeoastronomy* was advanced by Elizabeth Chesley Baity (following the suggestion of Euan MacKie) in 1973, but as a topic of study it may be much older, depending on how archaeoastronomy is defined.
[src:oar/archaeoastronomy-p01] Clive Ruggles says that Heinrich Nissen, working in the mid-nineteenth century was arguably the first archaeoastronomer.
[src:oar/archaeoastronomy-p01] Rolf Sinclair says that Norman Lockyer, working in the late 19th and early 20th centuries, could be called the 'father of archaeoastronomy'.
[src:oar/archaeoastronomy-p01] Euan MacKie would place the origin even later, stating: "...the genesis and modern flowering of archaeoastronomy must surely lie in the work of Alexander Thom in Britain between the 1930s and the 1970s".
[src:oar/archaeoastronomy-p01] In the 1960s the work of the engineer Alexander Thom and that of the astronomer Gerald Hawkins, who proposed that Stonehenge was a Neolithic computer, inspired new interest in the astronomical features of ancient sites.
[src:oar/archaeoastronomy-p01] The claims of Hawkins were largely dismissed, but this was not the case for Alexander Thom's work, whose survey results of megalithic sites hypothesized widespread practice of accurate astronomy in the British Isles.
[src:oar/archaeoastronomy-p01] Euan MacKie, recognizing that Thom's theories needed to be tested, excavated at the Kintraw standing stone site in Argyllshire in 1970 and 1971 to check whether the latter's prediction of an observation platform on the hill slope above the stone was correct.
[src:oar/archaeoastronomy-p01] There was an artificial platform there and this apparent verification of Thom's long alignment hypothesis (Kintraw was diagnosed as an accurate winter solstice site) led him to check Thom's geometrical theories at the Cultoon stone circle in Islay, also with a positive result.
[src:oar/archaeoastronomy-p01] MacKie therefore broadly accepted Thom's conclusions and published new prehistories of Britain.
[src:oar/archaeoastronomy-p01] In contrast a re-evaluation of Thom's fieldwork by Clive Ruggles argued that Thom's claims of high accuracy astronomy were not fully supported by the evidence.
[src:oar/archaeoastronomy-p01] Nevertheless, Thom's legacy remains strong, Edwin C.
[src:oar/archaeoastronomy-p01] The approach in the New World, where anthropologists began to consider more fully the role of astronomy in Amerindian civilizations, was markedly different.
[src:oar/archaeoastronomy-p01] They had access to sources that the prehistory of Europe lacks such as ethnographies and the historical records of the early colonizers.
[src:oar/archaeoastronomy-p01] Following the pioneering example of Anthony Aveni, this allowed New World archaeoastronomers to make claims for motives which in the Old World would have been mere speculation.
[src:oar/archaeoastronomy-p01] The concentration on historical data led to some claims of high accuracy that were comparatively weak when compared to the statistically led investigations in Europe.
[src:oar/archaeoastronomy-p01] This came to a head at a meeting sponsored by the International Astronomical Union (IAU) in Oxford in 1981.
[src:oar/archaeoastronomy-p01] The methodologies and research questions of the participants were considered so different that the conference proceedings were published as two volumes.
[src:oar/archaeoastronomy-p01] Nevertheless, the conference was considered a success in bringing researchers together and Oxford conferences have continued every four or five years at locations around the world.
[src:oar/archaeoastronomy-p01] Archaeoastronomy has long been seen as an interdisciplinary field that uses written and unwritten evidence to study the astronomies of other cultures.
[src:oar/archaeoastronomy-p01] Reflecting Archaeoastronomy's development as an interdisciplinary subject, research in the field is conducted by investigators trained in a wide range of disciplines.
[src:oar/archaeoastronomy-p01] Only rarely did they describe their work as astronomical, and then only as a secondary category.
[src:oar/archaeoastronomy-p01] Both practicing archaeoastronomers and observers of the discipline approach it from different perspectives.
[src:oar/archaeoastronomy-p01] The reactions of professional archaeologists to archaeoastronomy have been decidedly mixed.
[src:oar/archaeoastronomy-p01] Some expressed incomprehension or even hostility, varying from a rejection by the archaeological mainstream of what they saw as an archaeoastronomical fringe to an incomprehension between the cultural focus of archaeologists and the quantitative focus of early archaeoastronomers.
[src:oar/archaeoastronomy-p01] Yet archaeologists have increasingly come to incorporate many of the insights from archaeoastronomy into archaeology textbooks and, as mentioned above, some students wrote archaeology dissertations on archaeoastronomical topics.
[src:oar/archaeoastronomy-p01] Since archaeoastronomers disagree so widely on the characterization of the discipline, they even dispute its name.
[src:oar/archaeoastronomy-p01] All three major international scholarly associations relate archaeoastronomy to the study of culture, using the term *Astronomy in Culture* or a translation.
[src:oar/archaeoastronomy-p01] Michael Hoskin sees an important part of the discipline as fact-collecting, rather than theorizing, and proposed to label this aspect of the discipline *Archaeotopography.* Ruggles and Saunders proposed *Cultural Astronomy* as a unifying term for the various methods of studying folk astronomies.
[src:oar/archaeoastronomy-p01] Others have argued that astronomy is an inaccurate term, what are being studied are cosmologies and people who object to the use of logos have suggested adopting the Spanish *cosmovisión*.
[src:oar/archaeoastronomy-p01] When debates polarise between techniques, the methods are often referred to by a colour code, based on the colours of the bindings of the two volumes from the first Oxford Conference, where the approaches were first distinguished.
[src:oar/archaeoastronomy-p01] Green (Old World) archaeoastronomers rely heavily on statistics and are sometimes accused of missing the cultural context of what is a social practice.
[src:oar/archaeoastronomy-p01] Brown (New World) archaeoastronomers in contrast have abundant ethnographic and historical evidence and have been described as 'cavalier' on matters of measurement and statistical analysis.
[src:oar/archaeoastronomy-p01] Finding a way to integrate various approaches has been a subject of much discussion since the early 1990s.
[src:oar/archaeoastronomy-p01] There is no one way to do archaeoastronomy.
[src:oar/archaeoastronomy-p01] The divisions between archaeoastronomers tend not to be between the physical scientists and the social scientists.
[src:oar/archaeoastronomy-p01] Instead, it tends to depend on the location and/or kind of data available to the researcher.
[src:oar/archaeoastronomy-p01] In the Old World, there is little data but the sites themselves; in the New World, the sites were supplemented by ethnographic and historic data.
[src:oar/archaeoastronomy-p01] The effects of the isolated development of archaeoastronomy in different places can still often be seen in research today.
[src:oar/archaeoastronomy-p01] Research methods can be classified as falling into one of two approaches, though more recent projects often use techniques from both categories.
[src:oar/archaeoastronomy-p01] Green archaeoastronomy is named after the cover of the book *Archaeoastronomy in the Old World*.
[src:oar/archaeoastronomy-p01] It is based primarily on statistics and is particularly apt for prehistoric sites where the social evidence is relatively scant compared to the historic period.
[src:oar/archaeoastronomy-p01] The basic methods were developed by Alexander Thom during his extensive surveys of British megalithic sites.
[src:oar/archaeoastronomy-p01] Thom wished to examine whether or not prehistoric peoples used high-accuracy astronomy.
[src:oar/archaeoastronomy-p01] He believed that by using horizon astronomy, observers could make estimates of dates in the year to a specific day.
[src:oar/archaeoastronomy-p01] The observation required finding a place where on a specific date the Sun set into a notch on the horizon.
[src:oar/archaeoastronomy-p01] A common theme is a mountain that blocked the Sun, but on the right day would allow the tiniest fraction to re-emerge on the other side for a 'double sunset'.
[src:oar/archaeoastronomy-p01] The animation below shows two sunsets at a hypothetical site, one the day before the summer solstice and one at the summer solstice, which has a double sunset.
[src:oar/archaeoastronomy-p01] To test this idea he surveyed hundreds of stone rows and circles.
[src:oar/archaeoastronomy-p01] Any individual alignment could indicate a direction by chance, but he planned to show that together the distribution of alignments was non-random, showing that there was an astronomical intent to the orientation of at least some of the alignments.
[src:oar/archaeoastronomy-p01] His results indicated the existence of eight, sixteen, or perhaps even thirty-two approximately equal divisions of the year.
[src:oar/archaeoastronomy-p01] The two solstices, the two equinoxes and four cross-quarter days, days halfway between a solstice and the equinox were associated with the medieval Celtic calendar.
[src:oar/archaeoastronomy-p01] While not all these conclusions have been accepted, it has had an enduring influence on archaeoastronomy, especially in Europe.
[src:oar/archaeoastronomy-p01] Euan MacKie has supported Thom's analysis, to which he added an archaeological context by comparing Neolithic Britain to the Mayan civilization to argue for a stratified society in this period.
[src:oar/archaeoastronomy-p01] To test his ideas he conducted a couple of excavations at proposed prehistoric observatories in Scotland.
[src:oar/archaeoastronomy-p01] Kintraw is a site notable for its four-meter high standing stone.
[src:oar/archaeoastronomy-p01] Thom proposed that this was a foresight to a point on the distant horizon between Beinn Shianaidh and Beinn o'Chaolias on Jura.
[src:oar/archaeoastronomy-p01] This, Thom argued, was a notch on the horizon where a double sunset would occur at midwinter.
[src:oar/archaeoastronomy-p01] However, from ground level, this sunset would be obscured by a ridge in the landscape, and the viewer would need to be raised by two meters: another observation platform was needed.
[src:oar/archaeoastronomy-p01] This was identified across a gorge where a platform was formed from small stones.
[src:oar/archaeoastronomy-p01] In contrast Clive Ruggles has argued that there are problems with the selection of data in Thom's surveys.
[src:oar/archaeoastronomy-p01] Others have noted that the accuracy of horizon astronomy is limited by variations in refraction near the horizon.
[src:oar/archaeoastronomy-p01] The many records of native customs and beliefs made by Spanish chroniclers and ethnographic researchers means that brown archaeoastronomy is often associated with studies of astronomy in the Americas.
[src:oar/archaeoastronomy-p01] One famous site where historical records have been used to interpret sites is Chichen Itza.
[src:oar/archaeoastronomy-p01] Rather than analyzing the site and seeing which targets appear popular, archaeoastronomers have instead examined the ethnographic records to see what features of the sky were important to the Mayans and then sought archaeological correlates.
[src:oar/archaeoastronomy-p01] One example which could have been overlooked without historical records is the Mayan interest in the planet Venus.
[src:oar/archaeoastronomy-p01] This interest is attested to by the Dresden codex which contains tables with information about Venus's appearances in the sky.
[src:oar/archaeoastronomy-p01] These cycles would have been of astrological and ritual significance as Venus was associated with Quetzalcoatl or Xolotl.
[src:oar/archaeoastronomy-p01] Associations of architectural features with settings of Venus can be found in Chichen Itza, Uxmal, and probably some other Mesoamerican sites.
[src:oar/archaeoastronomy-p01] The Temple of the Warriors bears iconography depicting feathered serpents associated with Quetzalcoatl or Kukulcan.
[src:oar/archaeoastronomy-p01] This means that the building's alignment towards the place on the horizon where Venus first appears in the evening sky (when it coincides with the rainy season) may be meaningful.
[src:oar/archaeoastronomy-p01] However, since both the date and the azimuth of this event change continuously, a solar interpretation of this orientation is much more likely.
[src:oar/archaeoastronomy-p01] Anthony Aveni claims that another building associated with the planet Venus in the form of Kukulcan, and the rainy season at Chichen Itza is the Caracol.
[src:oar/archaeoastronomy-p01] This is a building with a circular tower and doors facing the cardinal directions.
[src:oar/archaeoastronomy-p01] The base faces the most northerly setting of Venus.
[src:oar/archaeoastronomy-p01] Additionally the pillars of a stylobate on the building's upper platform were painted black and red.
[src:oar/archaeoastronomy-p01] These are colours associated with Venus as an evening and morning star.
[src:oar/archaeoastronomy-p01] However the windows in the tower seem to have been little more than slots, making them poor at letting light in, but providing a suitable place to view out.
[src:oar/archaeoastronomy-p01] In their discussion of the credibility of archaeoastronomical sites, Cotte and Ruggles considered the interpretation that the Caracol is an observatory site was debated among specialists, meeting the second of their four levels of site credibility.
[src:oar/archaeoastronomy-p01] Aveni states that one of the strengths of the brown methodology is that it can explore astronomies invisible to statistical analysis and offers the astronomy of the Incas as another example.
[src:oar/archaeoastronomy-p01] The empire of the Incas was conceptually divided using *ceques*, radial routes emanating from the capital at Cusco.
[src:oar/archaeoastronomy-p01] In eastern Asia archaeoastronomy has developed from the history of astronomy and much archaeoastronomy is searching for material correlates of the historical record.
[src:oar/archaeoastronomy-p01] This is due to the rich historical record of astronomical phenomena which, in China, stretches back into the Han dynasty, in the second century BC.
[src:oar/archaeoastronomy-p01] A criticism of this method is that it can be statistically weak.
[src:oar/archaeoastronomy-p01] Schaefer in particular has questioned how robust the claimed alignments in the Caracol are.
[src:oar/archaeoastronomy-p01] Because of the wide variety of evidence, which can include artefacts as well as sites, there is no one way to practice archaeoastronomy.
[src:oar/archaeoastronomy-p01] Despite this it is accepted that archaeoastronomy is not a discipline that sits in isolation.
[src:oar/archaeoastronomy-p01] Because archaeoastronomy is an interdisciplinary field, whatever is being investigated should make sense both archaeologically and astronomically.
[src:oar/archaeoastronomy-p01] Studies are more likely to be considered sound if they use theoretical tools found in archaeology like analogy and homology and if they can demonstrate an understanding of accuracy and precision found in astronomy.
[src:oar/archaeoastronomy-p01] Both quantitative analyses and interpretations based on ethnographic analogies and other contextual evidence have recently been applied in systematic studies of architectural orientations in the Maya area and in other parts of Mesoamerica.
[src:oar/archaeoastronomy-p01] Because archaeoastronomy is about the many and various ways people interacted with the sky, there are a diverse range of sources giving information about astronomical practices.
[src:oar/archaeoastronomy-p01] A common source of data for archaeoastronomy is the study of alignments.
[src:oar/archaeoastronomy-p01] This is based on the assumption that the axis of alignment of an archaeological site is meaningfully oriented towards an astronomical target.
[src:oar/archaeoastronomy-p01] Brown archaeoastronomers may justify this assumption through reading historical or ethnographic sources, while green archaeoastronomers tend to prove that alignments are unlikely to be selected by chance, usually by demonstrating common patterns of alignment at multiple sites.
[src:oar/archaeoastronomy-p01] An alignment is calculated by measuring the azimuth, the angle from north, of the structure and the altitude of the horizon it faces The azimuth is usually measured using a theodolite or a compass.
[src:oar/archaeoastronomy-p01] A compass is easier to use, though the deviation of the Earth's magnetic field from true north, known as its magnetic declination must be taken into account.
[src:oar/archaeoastronomy-p01] Compasses are also unreliable in areas prone to magnetic interference, such as sites being supported by scaffolding.
[src:oar/archaeoastronomy-p01] Additionally a compass can only measure the azimuth to a precision of a half a degree.
[src:oar/archaeoastronomy-p01] A theodolite can be considerably more accurate if used correctly, but it is also considerably more difficult to use correctly.
[src:oar/archaeoastronomy-p01] There is no inherent way to align a theodolite with North and so the scale has to be calibrated using astronomical observation, usually the position of the Sun.
[src:oar/archaeoastronomy-p01] Because the position of celestial bodies changes with the time of day due to the Earth's rotation, the time of these calibration observations must be accurately known, or else there will be a systematic error in the measurements.
[src:oar/archaeoastronomy-p01] Horizon altitudes can be measured with a theodolite or a clinometer.
[src:oar/archaeoastronomy-p01] For artifacts such as the Sky Disc of Nebra, alleged to be a Bronze Age artefact depicting the cosmos, the analysis would be similar to typical post-excavation analysis as used in other sub-disciplines in archaeology.
[src:oar/archaeoastronomy-p01] An artefact is examined and attempts are made to draw analogies with historical or ethnographical records of other peoples.
[src:oar/archaeoastronomy-p01] The more parallels that can be found, the more likely an explanation is to be accepted by other archaeologists.
[src:oar/archaeoastronomy-p01] A more mundane example is the presence of astrological symbols found on some shoes and sandals from the Roman Empire.
[src:oar/archaeoastronomy-p01] The use of shoes and sandals is well known, but Carol van Driel-Murray has proposed that astrological symbols etched onto sandals gave the footwear spiritual or medicinal meanings.
[src:oar/archaeoastronomy-p01] This is supported through citation of other known uses of astrological symbols and their connection to medical practice and with the historical records of the time.
[src:oar/archaeoastronomy-p01] Another well-known artefact with an astronomical use is the Antikythera mechanism.
[src:oar/archaeoastronomy-p01] In this case analysis of the artefact, and reference to the description of similar devices described by Cicero, would indicate a plausible use for the device.
[src:oar/archaeoastronomy-p01] The argument is bolstered by the presence of symbols on the mechanism, allowing the disc to be read.
[src:oar/archaeoastronomy-p01] Art and inscriptions may not be confined to artefacts, but also appear painted or inscribed on an archaeological site.
[src:oar/archaeoastronomy-p01] Sometimes inscriptions are helpful enough to give instructions to a site's use.
[src:oar/archaeoastronomy-p01] For example, a Greek inscription on a stele (from Itanos) has been translated as:"Patron set this up for Zeus Epopsios.
[src:oar/archaeoastronomy-p01] Should anyone wish to know: off 'the little pig' and the stele the sun turns." From Mesoamerica come Mayan and Aztec codices.
[src:oar/archaeoastronomy-p01] These are folding books made from Amatl, processed tree bark on which are glyphs in Mayan or Aztec script.
[src:oar/archaeoastronomy-p01] The Dresden codex contains information regarding the Venus cycle, confirming its importance to the Mayans.
[src:oar/archaeoastronomy-p01] More problematic are those cases where the movement of the Sun at different times and seasons causes light and shadow interactions with petroglyphs.
[src:oar/archaeoastronomy-p01] A widely known example is the Sun Dagger of Fajada Butte at which a glint of sunlight passes over a spiral petroglyph.
[src:oar/archaeoastronomy-p01] The location of a dagger of light on the petroglyph varies throughout the year.
[src:oar/archaeoastronomy-p01] At the summer solstice a dagger can be seen through the heart of the spiral; at the winter solstice two daggers appear to either side of it.
[src:oar/archaeoastronomy-p01] It is proposed that this petroglyph was created to mark these events.
[src:oar/archaeoastronomy-p01] Recent studies have identified many similar sites in the US Southwest and Northwestern Mexico.
[src:oar/archaeoastronomy-p01] It has been argued that the number of solstitial markers at these sites provides statistical evidence that they were intended to mark the solstices.
[src:oar/archaeoastronomy-p01] The Sun Dagger site on Fajada Butte in Chaco Canyon, New Mexico, stands out for its explicit light markings that record all the key events of both the solar and lunar cycles: summer solstice, winter solstice, equinox, and the major and minor lunar standstills of the Moon's 18.6 year cycle.
[src:oar/archaeoastronomy-p01] In addition at two other sites on Fajada Butte, there are five light markings on petroglyphs recording the summer and winter solstices, equinox and solar noon.
[src:oar/archaeoastronomy-p01] Numerous buildings and interbuilding alignments of the great houses of Chaco Canyon and outlying areas are oriented to the same solar and lunar directions that are marked at the Sun Dagger site.
[src:oar/archaeoastronomy-p01] If no ethnographic nor historical data are found which can support this assertion then acceptance of the idea relies upon whether or not there are enough petroglyph sites in North America that such a correlation could occur by chance.
[src:oar/archaeoastronomy-p01] It is helpful when petroglyphs are associated with existing peoples.
[src:oar/archaeoastronomy-p01] This allows ethnoastronomers to question informants as to the meaning of such symbols.
[src:oar/archaeoastronomy-p01] As well as the materials left by peoples themselves, there are also the reports of other who have encountered them.
[src:oar/archaeoastronomy-p01] The historical records of the Conquistadores are a rich source of information about the pre-Columbian Americans.
[src:oar/archaeoastronomy-p01] Ethnographers also provide material about many other peoples.
[src:oar/archaeoastronomy-p01] Anthony Aveni uses the importance of zenith passages as an example of the importance of ethnography.
[src:oar/archaeoastronomy-p01] For peoples living between the tropics of Cancer and Capricorn there are two days of the year when the noon Sun passes directly overhead and casts no shadow.
[src:oar/archaeoastronomy-p01] In parts of Mesoamerica this was considered a significant day as it would herald the arrival of rains, and so play a part in the cycle of agriculture.
[src:oar/archaeoastronomy-p01] This knowledge is still considered important amongst Mayan Indians living in Central America today.
[src:oar/archaeoastronomy-p01] The ethnographic records suggested to archaeoastronomers that this day may have been important to the ancient Mayans.
[src:oar/archaeoastronomy-p01] There are also shafts known as 'zenith tubes' which illuminate subterranean rooms when the Sun passes overhead found at places like Monte Albán and Xochicalco.
[src:oar/archaeoastronomy-p01] It is only through the ethnography that we can speculate that the timing of the illumination was considered important in Mayan society.
[src:oar/archaeoastronomy-p01] Alignments to the sunrise and sunset on the day of the zenith passage have been claimed to exist at several sites.
[src:oar/archaeoastronomy-p01] However, it has been shown that, since there are very few orientations that can be related to these phenomena, they likely have different explanations.
[src:oar/archaeoastronomy-p01] Ethnographies also caution against over-interpretation of sites.
[src:oar/archaeoastronomy-p01] At a site in Chaco Canyon can be found a pictograph with a star, crescent and hand.
[src:oar/archaeoastronomy-p01] It has been argued by some astronomers that this is a record of the 1054 Supernova.
[src:oar/archaeoastronomy-p01] However recent reexaminations of related 'supernova petroglyphs' raises questions about such sites in general.
[src:oar/archaeoastronomy-p01] Cotte and Ruggles used the Supernova petroglyph as an example of a completely refuted site and anthropological evidence suggests other interpretations.
[src:oar/archaeoastronomy-p01] The Zuni people, who claim a strong ancestral affiliation with Chaco, marked their sun-watching station with a crescent, star, hand and sundisc, similar to those found at the Chaco site.
[src:oar/archaeoastronomy-p01] Ethnoastronomy is also an important field outside of the Americas.
[src:oar/archaeoastronomy-p01] For example, anthropological work with Aboriginal Australians is producing much information about their Indigenous astronomies and about their interaction with the modern world.
[src:oar/archaeoastronomy-p01] Once the researcher has data to test, it is often necessary to attempt to recreate ancient sky conditions to place the data in its historical environment.
[src:oar/archaeoastronomy-p01] To calculate what astronomical features a structure faced, a coordinate system is needed, and the stars provide such a system.
[src:oar/archaeoastronomy-p01] On a clear night observe the stars spinning around the celestial pole can be observed.
[src:oar/archaeoastronomy-p01] This point is +90° of the North Celestial Pole or −90° observing the Southern Celestial Pole.
[src:oar/archaeoastronomy-p01] The concentric circles the stars trace out are lines of celestial latitude, known as *declination*.
[src:oar/archaeoastronomy-p01] The arc connecting the points on the horizon due East and due West (if the horizon is flat) and all points midway between the Celestial Poles is the Celestial Equator which has a declination of 0°.
[src:oar/archaeoastronomy-p01] The visible declinations vary depending where you are on the globe.
[src:oar/archaeoastronomy-p01] Only an observer on the North Pole of Earth would be unable to see any stars from the Southern Celestial Hemisphere at night (see diagram below).
[src:oar/archaeoastronomy-p01] Once a declination has been found for the point on the horizon that a building faces it is then possible to say whether a specific body can be seen in that direction.
[src:oar/archaeoastronomy-p01] While the stars are fixed to their declinations the Sun is not.
[src:oar/archaeoastronomy-p01] The rising point of the Sun varies throughout the year.
[src:oar/archaeoastronomy-p01] It swings between two limits marked by the solstices a bit like a pendulum, slowing as it reaches the extremes, but passing rapidly through the midpoint.
[src:oar/archaeoastronomy-p01] If an archaeoastronomer can calculate from the azimuth and horizon height that a site was built to view a declination of +23.5° then he or she need not wait until 21 June to confirm the site does indeed face the summer solstice.
[src:oar/archaeoastronomy-p01] For more information see History of solar observation.
[src:oar/archaeoastronomy-p01] The Moon's appearance is considerably more complex.
[src:oar/archaeoastronomy-p01] Its motion, like the Sun, is between two limits—known as *luni*stices rather than *sol*stices.
[src:oar/archaeoastronomy-p01] However, its travel between lunistices is considerably faster.
[src:oar/archaeoastronomy-p01] It takes a sidereal month to complete its cycle rather than the year-long trek of the Sun.
[src:oar/archaeoastronomy-p01] This is further complicated as the lunistices marking the limits of the Moon's movement move on an 18.6 year cycle.
[src:oar/archaeoastronomy-p01] For slightly over nine years the extreme limits of the Moon are outside the range of sunrise.
[src:oar/archaeoastronomy-p01] For the remaining half of the cycle the Moon never exceeds the limits of the range of sunrise.
[src:oar/archaeoastronomy-p01] However, much lunar observation was concerned with the *phase* of the Moon.
[src:oar/archaeoastronomy-p01] The cycle from one New Moon to the next runs on an entirely different cycle, the Synodic month.
[src:oar/archaeoastronomy-p01] Thus when examining sites for lunar significance the data can appear sparse due to the extremely variable nature of the Moon.
[src:oar/archaeoastronomy-p01] Finally there is often a need to correct for the apparent movement of the stars.
[src:oar/archaeoastronomy-p01] On the timescale of human civilisation the stars have largely maintained the same position relative to each other.
[src:oar/archaeoastronomy-p01] Each night they appear to rotate around the celestial poles due to the Earth's rotation about its axis.
[src:oar/archaeoastronomy-p01] However, the Earth spins rather like a spinning top.
[src:oar/archaeoastronomy-p01] Not only does the Earth rotate, it wobbles.
[src:oar/archaeoastronomy-p01] The Earth's axis takes around 25,800 years to complete one full wobble.
[src:oar/archaeoastronomy-p01] The effect to the archaeoastronomer is that stars did not rise over the horizon in the past in the same places as they do today.
[src:oar/archaeoastronomy-p01] Nor did the stars rotate around Polaris as they do now.
[src:oar/archaeoastronomy-p01] The movement of the Earth's axis was already noticed by the Sumerians over six thousand years ago, when they were able to observe the star Canopus culminating directly above the horizon on the southern meridian for the first time in their oldest and southernmost city Eridu.
[src:oar/archaeoastronomy-p01] For several decades, Canopus was not yet visible in the neighbouring town of Ur to the north-east of Eridu, and therefore, it was called the "Star of the City of Eridu" in Sumerian.
[src:oar/archaeoastronomy-p01] In the case of the Egyptian pyramids, it has been shown they were aligned towards Thuban, a faint star in the constellation of Draco.
[src:oar/archaeoastronomy-p01] The effect can be substantial over relatively short lengths of time, historically speaking.
[src:oar/archaeoastronomy-p01] For instance a person born on 25 December in Roman times would have been born with the Sun in the constellation Capricorn.
[src:oar/archaeoastronomy-p01] In the modern period a person born on the same date would have the Sun in Sagittarius due to the precession of the equinoxes.
[src:oar/archaeoastronomy-p01] Additionally there are often transient phenomena, events which do not happen on an annual cycle.
[src:oar/archaeoastronomy-p01] Most predictable are events like eclipses.
[src:oar/archaeoastronomy-p01] In the case of solar eclipses these can be used to date events in the past.
[src:oar/archaeoastronomy-p01] A solar eclipse mentioned by Herodotus enables us to date a battle between the Medes and the Lydians, which following the eclipse failed to happen, to 28 May, 585 BC.
[src:oar/archaeoastronomy-p01] Some comets are predictable, most famously Halley's Comet.
[src:oar/archaeoastronomy-p01] Yet as a class of object they remain unpredictable and can appear at any time.
[src:oar/archaeoastronomy-p01] Some have extremely lengthy orbital periods which means their past appearances and returns cannot be predicted.
[src:oar/archaeoastronomy-p01] Others may have only ever passed through the Solar System once and so are inherently unpredictable.
[src:oar/archaeoastronomy-p01] Meteor showers should be predictable, but some meteors are cometary debris and so require calculations of orbits which are currently impossible to complete.
[src:oar/archaeoastronomy-p01] Other events noted by ancients include aurorae, sun dogs and rainbows all of which are as impossible to predict as the ancient weather, but nevertheless may have been considered important phenomena.
[src:oar/archaeoastronomy-p01] A common justification for the need for astronomy is the need to develop an accurate calendar for agricultural reasons.
[src:oar/archaeoastronomy-p01] Ancient texts like Hesiod's Works and Days, an ancient farming manual, would appear to partially confirm this: astronomical observations are used in combination with ecological signs, such as bird migrations to determine the seasons.
[src:oar/archaeoastronomy-p01] Ethnoastronomical studies of the Hopi of the southwestern United States indicate that they carefully observed the rising and setting positions of the Sun to determine the proper times to plant crops.
[src:oar/archaeoastronomy-p01] However, ethnoastronomical work with the Mursi of Ethiopia shows that their luni-solar calendar was somewhat haphazard, indicating the limits of astronomical calendars in some societies.
[src:oar/archaeoastronomy-p01] All the same, calendars appear to be an almost universal phenomenon in societies as they provide tools for the regulation of communal activities.
[src:oar/archaeoastronomy-p01] One such example is the *Tzolk'in* calendar of 260 days.
[src:oar/archaeoastronomy-p01] Together with the 365-day year, it was used in pre-Columbian Mesoamerica, forming part of a comprehensive calendrical system, which combined a series of astronomical observations and ritual cycles.
[src:oar/archaeoastronomy-p01] Archaeoastronomical studies throughout Mesoamerica have shown that the orientations of most structures refer to the Sun and were used in combination with the 260-day cycle for scheduling agricultural activities and the accompanying rituals.
[src:oar/archaeoastronomy-p01] The distribution of dates and intervals marked by orientations of monumental ceremonial complexes in the area along the southern Gulf Coast in Mexico, dated to about 1100 to 700 BCE, represents the earliest evidence of the use of this cycle.
[src:oar/archaeoastronomy-p01] Other peculiar calendars include ancient Greek calendars.
[src:oar/archaeoastronomy-p01] These were nominally lunar, starting with the New Moon.
[src:oar/archaeoastronomy-p01] In reality the calendar could pause or skip days with confused citizens inscribing dates by both the civic calendar and *ton theoi*, by the moon.
[src:oar/archaeoastronomy-p01] The lack of any universal calendar for ancient Greece suggests that coordination of panhellenic events such as games or rituals could be difficult and that astronomical symbolism may have been used as a politically neutral form of timekeeping.
[src:oar/archaeoastronomy-p01] Orientation measurements in Greek temples and Byzantine churches have been associated to deity's name day, festivities, and special events.
[src:oar/archaeoastronomy-p01] Another motive for studying the sky is to understand and explain the universe.
[src:oar/archaeoastronomy-p01] In these cultures myth was a tool for achieving this, and the explanations, while not reflecting the standards of modern science, are cosmologies.
[src:oar/archaeoastronomy-p01] The Incas arranged their empire to demonstrate their cosmology.
[src:oar/archaeoastronomy-p01] The capital, Cusco, was at the centre of the empire and connected to it by means of ceques, conceptually straight lines radiating out from the centre.
[src:oar/archaeoastronomy-p01] These ceques connected the centre of the empire to the four *suyus*, which were regions defined by their direction from Cusco.
[src:oar/archaeoastronomy-p01] The notion of a quartered cosmos is common across the Andes.
[src:oar/archaeoastronomy-p01] Gary Urton, who has conducted fieldwork in the Andean villagers of Misminay, has connected this quartering with the appearance of the Milky Way in the night sky.
[src:oar/archaeoastronomy-p01] In one season it will bisect the sky and in another bisect it in a perpendicular fashion.
[src:oar/archaeoastronomy-p01] The importance of observing cosmological factors is also seen on the other side of the world.
[src:oar/archaeoastronomy-p01] The Forbidden City in Beijing is laid out to follow cosmic order though rather than observing four directions.
[src:oar/archaeoastronomy-p01] The Chinese system was composed of five directions: North, South, East, West and Centre.
[src:oar/archaeoastronomy-p01] The Forbidden City occupied the centre of ancient Beijing.
[src:oar/archaeoastronomy-p01] One approaches the Emperor from the south, thus placing him in front of the circumpolar stars.
[src:oar/archaeoastronomy-p01] This creates the situation of the heavens revolving around the person of the Emperor.
[src:oar/archaeoastronomy-p01] The Chinese cosmology is now better known through its export as feng shui.
[src:oar/archaeoastronomy-p01] There is also much information about how the universe was thought to work stored in the mythology of the constellations.
[src:oar/archaeoastronomy-p01] The Barasana of the Amazon plan part of their annual cycle based on observation of the stars.
[src:oar/archaeoastronomy-p01] When their constellation of the Caterpillar-Jaguar (roughly equivalent to the modern Scorpius) falls they prepare to catch the pupating caterpillars of the forest as they fall from the trees.
[src:oar/archaeoastronomy-p01] The caterpillars provide food at a season when other foods are scarce.
[src:oar/archaeoastronomy-p01] The Northern Dene peoples of Alaska and northwestern Canada recognize Traveller constellations that incorporate large portions of the night sky.
[src:oar/archaeoastronomy-p01] These constellations represent a culture hero known as the Traveller who, according to oral tradition, journeyed around the world before his spirit became embodied in the stars.
[src:oar/archaeoastronomy-p01] The constellations are composed of multiple smaller star groups named using body-part terminology, with the Milky Way identified as the Traveller's trail.
[src:oar/archaeoastronomy-p01] Knowledge of these constellations is traditionally acquired through personal discovery rather than direct instruction, and they serve roles in navigation, timekeeping, and spiritual practice.
[src:oar/archaeoastronomy-p01] A more well-known source of constellation myth are the texts of the Greeks and Romans.
[src:oar/archaeoastronomy-p01] The origin of their constellations remains a matter of vigorous and occasionally fractious debate.
[src:oar/archaeoastronomy-p01] The loss of one of the sisters, Merope, in some Greek myths may reflect an astronomical event wherein one of the stars in the Pleiades disappeared from view by the naked eye.
[src:oar/archaeoastronomy-p01] The chaos, monsters and violence in ancient myths are representative of the forces that shape each age.
[src:oar/archaeoastronomy-p01] They argued that ancient myths are the remains of preliterate, late Neolithic astronomy that was lost.
[src:oar/archaeoastronomy-p01] Santillana and von Dechend argued in their book *Hamlet's Mill: An Essay on Myth and the Frame of Time* (1969) that ancient myths have no historical or factual basis other than a cosmological one encoding astronomical phenomena, especially the precession of the equinoxes.
[src:oar/archaeoastronomy-p01] Santillana and von Dechend's approach is not widely accepted.
[src:oar/archaeoastronomy-p01] By including celestial motifs in clothing it becomes possible for the wearer to make claims the power on Earth is drawn from above.
[src:oar/archaeoastronomy-p01] It has been said that the Shield of Achilles described by Homer is also a catalogue of constellations.
[src:oar/archaeoastronomy-p01] In North America shields depicted in Comanche petroglyphs appear to include Venus symbolism.
[src:oar/archaeoastronomy-p01] Solsticial alignments also can be seen as displays of power.
[src:oar/archaeoastronomy-p01] When viewed from a ceremonial plaza on the Island of the Sun (the mythical origin place of the Sun) in Lake Titicaca, the Sun was seen to rise at the June solstice between two towers on a nearby ridge.
[src:oar/archaeoastronomy-p01] The sacred part of the island was separated from the remainder of it by a stone wall and ethnographic records indicate that access to the sacred space was restricted to members of the Inca ruling elite.
[src:oar/archaeoastronomy-p01] Ordinary pilgrims stood on a platform outside the ceremonial area to see the solstice Sun rise between the towers.
[src:oar/archaeoastronomy-p01] In Egypt the temple of Amun-Re at Karnak has been the subject of much study.
[src:oar/archaeoastronomy-p01] Evaluation of the site, taking into account the change over time of the obliquity of the ecliptic show that the Great Temple was aligned on the rising of the midwinter Sun.
[src:oar/archaeoastronomy-p01] The length of the corridor down which sunlight would travel would have limited illumination at other times of the year.
[src:oar/archaeoastronomy-p01] In a later period the Serapeum of Alexandria was also said to have contained a solar alignment so that, on a specific sunrise, a shaft of light would pass across the lips of the statue of Serapis thus symbolising the Sun saluting the god.
[src:oar/archaeoastronomy-p02] Clive Ruggles and Michel Cotte recently edited a book on heritage sites of astronomy and archaeoastronomy which discussed a worldwide sample of astronomical and archaeoastronomical sites and provided criteria for the classification of archaeoastronomical sites.
[src:oar/archaeoastronomy-p02] Newgrange is a passage tomb in the Republic of Ireland dating from around 3,300 to 2,900 BC For a few days around the Winter Solstice light shines along the central passageway into the heart of the tomb.
[src:oar/archaeoastronomy-p02] What makes this notable is not that light shines in the passageway, but that it does not do so through the main entrance.
[src:oar/archaeoastronomy-p02] Instead it enters via a hollow box above the main doorway discovered by Michael O'Kelly.
[src:oar/archaeoastronomy-p02] It is this roofbox which strongly indicates that the tomb was built with an astronomical aspect in mind.
[src:oar/archaeoastronomy-p02] In their discussion of the credibility of archaeoastronomical sites, Cotte and Ruggles gave Newgrange as an example of a Generally accepted site, the highest of their four levels of credibility.
[src:oar/archaeoastronomy-p02] Since the first modern measurements of the precise cardinal orientations of the Giza pyramids by Flinders Petrie, various astronomical methods have been proposed for the original establishment of these orientations.
[src:oar/archaeoastronomy-p02] It was recently proposed that this was done by observing the positions of two stars in the Plough / Big Dipper which was known to Egyptians as the thigh.
[src:oar/archaeoastronomy-p02] It is thought that a vertical alignment between these two stars checked with a plumb bob was used to ascertain where north lay.
[src:oar/archaeoastronomy-p02] The deviations from true north using this model reflect the accepted dates of construction.
[src:oar/archaeoastronomy-p02] Some have argued that the pyramids were laid out as a map of the three stars in the belt of Orion, although this theory has been criticized by reputable astronomers.
[src:oar/archaeoastronomy-p02] The site was instead probably governed by a spectacular hierophany which occurs at the summer solstice, when the Sun, viewed from the Sphinx terrace, forms—together with the two giant pyramids—the symbol Akhet, which was also the name of the Great Pyramid.
[src:oar/archaeoastronomy-p02] Further, the south east corners of all the three pyramids align towards the temple of Heliopolis, as first discovered by the Egyptologist Mark Lehner.
[src:oar/archaeoastronomy-p02] The astronomical ceiling of the tomb of Senenmut (c.
[src:oar/archaeoastronomy-p02] 1470 BC) contains the Celestial Diagram depicting circumpolar constellations in the form of discs.
[src:oar/archaeoastronomy-p02] Each disc is divided into 24 sections suggesting a 24-hour time period.
[src:oar/archaeoastronomy-p02] Constellations are portrayed as sacred deities of Egypt.
[src:oar/archaeoastronomy-p02] The observation of lunar cycles is also evident.
[src:oar/archaeoastronomy-p02] El Castillo, also known as Kukulcán's Pyramid, is a Mesoamerican step-pyramid built in the centre of Mayan center of Chichen Itza in Mexico.
[src:oar/archaeoastronomy-p02] Several architectural features have suggested astronomical elements.
[src:oar/archaeoastronomy-p02] Each of the stairways built into the sides of the pyramid has 91 steps.
[src:oar/archaeoastronomy-p02] Along with the extra one for the platform at the top, this totals 365 steps, which is possibly one for each day of the year (365.25) or the number of lunar orbits in 10,000 rotations (365.01).
[src:oar/archaeoastronomy-p02] A visually striking effect is seen every March and September as an unusual shadow occurs around the equinoxes.
[src:oar/archaeoastronomy-p02] Light and shadow phenomena have been proposed to explain a possible architectural hierophany involving the sun at Chichén Itzá in a Maya Toltec structure dating to about 1000 CE.
[src:oar/archaeoastronomy-p02] A shadow appears to descend the west balustrade of the northern stairway.
[src:oar/archaeoastronomy-p02] The visual effect is of a serpent descending the stairway, with its head at the base in light.
[src:oar/archaeoastronomy-p02] Additionally the western face points to sunset around 25 May, traditionally the date of transition from the dry to the rainy season.
[src:oar/archaeoastronomy-p02] The intended alignment was, however, likely incorporated in the northern (main) facade of the temple, as it corresponds to sunsets on May 20 and July 24, recorded also by the central axis of Castillo at Tulum.
[src:oar/archaeoastronomy-p02] The two dates are separated by 65 and 300 days, and it has been shown that the solar orientations in Mesoamerica regularly correspond to dates separated by calendrically significant intervals (multiples of 13 and 20 days).
[src:oar/archaeoastronomy-p02] In their discussion of the credibility of archaeoastronomical sites, Cotte and Ruggles used the "equinox hierophany" at Chichén Itzá as an example of an Unproven site, the third of their four levels of credibility.
[src:oar/archaeoastronomy-p02] Many astronomical alignments have been claimed for Stonehenge, a complex of megaliths and earthworks in the Salisbury Plain of England.
[src:oar/archaeoastronomy-p02] The most famous of these is the midsummer alignment, where the Sun rises over the Heel Stone.
[src:oar/archaeoastronomy-p02] However, this interpretation has been challenged by some archaeologists who argue that the midwinter alignment, where the viewer is outside Stonehenge and sees the Sun setting in the henge, is the more significant alignment, and the midsummer alignment may be a coincidence due to local topography.
[src:oar/archaeoastronomy-p02] In their discussion of the credibility of archaeoastronomical sites, Cotte and Ruggles gave Stonehenge as an example of a Generally accepted site, the highest of their four levels of credibility.
[src:oar/archaeoastronomy-p02] As well as solar alignments, there are proposed lunar alignments.
[src:oar/archaeoastronomy-p02] The four station stones mark out a rectangle.
[src:oar/archaeoastronomy-p02] The short sides point towards the midsummer sunrise and midwinter sunset.
[src:oar/archaeoastronomy-p02] The long sides if viewed towards the south-east, face the most southerly rising of the Moon.
[src:oar/archaeoastronomy-p02] Anthony Aveni notes that these lunar alignments have never gained the acceptance that the solar alignments have received.
[src:oar/archaeoastronomy-p02] This is an architecturally outstanding Neolithic chambered tomb on the mainland of Orkney, Scotland—probably dating to the early 3rd millennium BC, and where the setting Sun at midwinter shines down the entrance passage into the central chamber (see Newgrange).
[src:oar/archaeoastronomy-p02] In the 1990s further investigations were carried out to discover whether this was an accurate or an approximate solar alignment.
[src:oar/archaeoastronomy-p02] Several new aspects of the site were discovered.
[src:oar/archaeoastronomy-p02] In the first place the entrance passage faces the hills of the island Hoy, about 10 miles away.
[src:oar/archaeoastronomy-p02] Secondly, it consists of two straight lengths, angled at a few degrees to each other.
[src:oar/archaeoastronomy-p02] Thirdly, the outer part is aligned towards the midwinter sunset position on a level horizon just to the left of Ward Hill on Hoy.
[src:oar/archaeoastronomy-p02] Fourthly the inner part points directly at the Barnhouse standing stone about 400m away and then to the right end of the summit of Ward Hill, just before it dips down to the notch between it at Cuilags to the right.
[src:oar/archaeoastronomy-p02] This indicated line points to sunset on the first Sixteenths of the solar year (according to A.
[src:oar/archaeoastronomy-p02] Thom) before and after the winter solstice and the notch at the base of the right slope of the Hill is at the same declination.
[src:oar/archaeoastronomy-p02] Fourthly a similar 'double sunset' phenomenon is seen at the right end of Cuilags, also on Hoy; here the date is the first Eighth of the year before and after the winter solstice, at the beginning of November and February respectively—the Old Celtic festivals of Samhain and Imbolc.
[src:oar/archaeoastronomy-p02] This alignment is not indicated by an artificial structure but gains plausibility from the other two indicated lines.
[src:oar/archaeoastronomy-p02] Maeshowe is thus an extremely sophisticated calendar site which must have been positioned carefully in order to use the horizon foresights in the ways described.
[src:oar/archaeoastronomy-p02] Uxmal is a Mayan city in the Puuc Hills of Yucatán Peninsula, Mexico.
[src:oar/archaeoastronomy-p02] The Governor's Palace at Uxmal is often used as an exemplar of why it is important to combine ethnographic and alignment data.
[src:oar/archaeoastronomy-p02] The palace is aligned with an azimuth of 118° on the pyramid of Cehtzuc.
[src:oar/archaeoastronomy-p02] This alignment corresponds approximately to the southernmost rising and, with a much greater precision, to the northernmost setting of Venus; both phenomena occur once every eight years.
[src:oar/archaeoastronomy-p02] By itself this would not be sufficient to argue for a meaningful connection between the two events.
[src:oar/archaeoastronomy-p02] The palace has to be aligned in one direction or another and why should the rising of Venus be any more important than the rising of the Sun, Moon, other planets, Sirius *et cetera*?
[src:oar/archaeoastronomy-p02] The answer given is that not only does the palace point towards significant points of Venus, it is also covered in glyphs which stand for Venus and Mayan zodiacal constellations.
[src:oar/archaeoastronomy-p02] Moreover, the great northerly extremes of Venus always occur in late April or early May, coinciding with the onset of the rainy season.
[src:oar/archaeoastronomy-p02] The Venus glyphs placed in the cheeks of the Maya rain god Chac, most likely referring to the concomitance of these phenomena, support the west-working orientation scheme.
[src:oar/archaeoastronomy-p02] In Chaco Canyon, the center of the ancient Pueblo culture in the American Southwest, numerous solar and lunar light markings and architectural and road alignments have been documented.
[src:oar/archaeoastronomy-p02] These findings date to the 1977 discovery of the Sun Dagger site by Anna Sofaer.
[src:oar/archaeoastronomy-p02] Three large stone slabs leaning against a cliff channel light and shadow markings onto two spiral petroglyphs on the cliff wall, marking the solstices, equinoxes and the lunar standstills of the 18.6 year cycle of the moon.
[src:oar/archaeoastronomy-p02] Subsequent research by the Solstice Project and others demonstrated that numerous building and interbuilding alignments of the great houses of Chaco Canyon are oriented to solar, lunar and cardinal directions.
[src:oar/archaeoastronomy-p02] In addition, research shows that the Great North Road, a thirty-five mile engineered "road", was constructed not for utilitarian purposes but rather to connect the ceremonial center of Chaco Canyon with the direction north.
[src:oar/archaeoastronomy-p02] In recent years, new research has suggested that the Lascaux cave paintings in France may incorporate prehistoric star charts.
[src:oar/archaeoastronomy-p02] Michael Rappenglueck of LMU Munich argues that some of the non-figurative dot clusters and dots within some of the figurative images correlate with the constellations of Taurus, the Pleiades and the grouping known as the "Summer Triangle".
[src:oar/archaeoastronomy-p02] Applying phylogenetics to myths of the Cosmic Hunt, Julien d'Huy suggested that the palaeolithic version of this story could be the following: there is an animal that is a horned herbivore, especially an elk.
[src:oar/archaeoastronomy-p02] The animal is alive when it is transformed into a constellation.
[src:oar/archaeoastronomy-p02] Archaeoastronomy owes something of a poor reputation among scholars due to its occasional misuse to advance a range of pseudo-historical accounts.
[src:oar/archaeoastronomy-p02] Reuter compiled a study entitled *Germanische Himmelskunde*, or "Teutonic Skylore".
[src:oar/archaeoastronomy-p02] The astronomical orientations of ancient monuments claimed by Reuter and his followers would place the ancient Germanic peoples ahead of the Ancient Near East in the field of astronomy, demonstrating the intellectual superiority of the "Aryans" (Indo-Europeans) over the Semites.
[src:oar/archaeoastronomy-p02] Fell interpreted inscriptions in West Virginia as a description in Celtic Ogham alphabet of the supposed winter solstitial marker at the site.
[src:oar/archaeoastronomy-p02] The controversial translation was supposedly validated by a problematic archaeoastronomical indication in which the winter solstice Sun shone on an inscription of the Sun at the site.
[src:oar/archaeoastronomy-p02] Subsequent analyses criticized its cultural inappropriateness, as well as its linguistic and archaeoastronomical claims, to describe it as an example of "cult archaeology".
[src:oar/archaeoastronomy-p02] Archaeoastronomy is sometimes related to the fringe discipline of Archaeocryptography, when its followers attempt to find underlying mathematical orders beneath the proportions, size, and placement of archaeoastronomical sites such as Stonehenge and the Pyramid of Kukulcán at Chichen Itza.
[src:oar/archaeoastronomy-p02] Since the 19th century, numerous scholars have sought to use archaeoastronomical calculations to demonstrate the antiquity of Ancient Indian Vedic culture, computing the dates of astronomical observations ambiguously described in ancient poetry to as early as 4000 BC.
[src:oar/archaeoastronomy-p02] David Pingree, a historian of Indian astronomy, condemned "the scholars who perpetrate wild theories of prehistoric science and call themselves archaeoastronomers".
[src:oar/archaeoastronomy-p02] There are currently several academic organisations for scholars of archaeoastronomy (including ethnoastronomy and Indigenous astronomy).
[src:oar/archaeoastronomy-p02] ISAAC – the International Society for Archaeoastronomy and Astronomy in Culture – was founded in 1996 as the global society for the field.
[src:oar/archaeoastronomy-p02] It sponsors the Oxford conferences and the Journal of Astronomy in Culture.
[src:oar/archaeoastronomy-p02] SEAC – La Société Européenne pour l'Astronomie dans la Culture – was founded in 1992 with a focus on broader Europe.
[src:oar/archaeoastronomy-p02] SEAC holds annual conferences in Europe and publishes refereed conference proceedings on an annual basis.
[src:oar/archaeoastronomy-p02] SIAC – La Sociedad Interamericana de Astronomía en la Cultura was founded in 2003 with a focus on Latin America.
[src:oar/archaeoastronomy-p02] SCAAS - The Society for Cultural Astronomy in the American Southwest was founded in 2009 as a regional organisation focusing on the astronomies of the native peoples of the Southwestern United States; it has since held seven meetings and workshops.
[src:oar/archaeoastronomy-p02] AAAC – the Australian Association for Astronomy in Culture was founded in 2020 in Australia, focusing on Aboriginal and Torres Strait Islander astronomy.
[src:oar/archaeoastronomy-p02] The Romanian Society for Cultural Astronomy was founded in 2019, holding an annual international conference and publishing the first monograph on archaeo- and ethnoastronomy in Romania (2019).
[src:oar/archaeoastronomy-p02] SMART – the Society of Māori Astronomy Research and Traditions was founded in Aotearoa/New Zealand in 2013, focusing on Maori astronomy.
[src:oar/archaeoastronomy-p02] Native Skywatchers was founded in 2007 in Minnesota, USA to promote Native American star knowledge, particularly of the Lakota and Ojibwe peoples of the northern US and Canada.
[src:oar/archaeoastronomy-p02] Additionally the *Journal for the History of Astronomy* publishes many archaeoastronomical papers.
[src:oar/archaeoastronomy-p02] For twenty-seven volumes (from 1979 to 2002) it published an annual supplement *Archaeoastronomy*.
[src:oar/archaeoastronomy-p02] The *Journal of Astronomical History and Heritage*, *Culture & Cosmos*, and the *Journal of Skyscape Archaeology* also publish papers on archaeoastronomy.
[src:oar/archaeoastronomy-p02] National projects and university programs including, or dedicated to, cultural astronomy are found globally.
[src:oar/archaeoastronomy-p02] The Sophia Centre for Cosmology in Culture at the University of Wales - Trinity Saint David in Lampeter, UK.
[src:oar/archaeoastronomy-p02] The Cultural Astronomy Program at the University of Melbourne in Australia.
[src:oar/archaeoastronomy-p02] The Tata Institute of Fundamental Research made interesting findings in this field.
[src:oar/archaeological-culture] An **archaeological culture** is a recurring assemblage of types of artifacts, buildings, and monuments from a specific period and region that may constitute the material culture remains of a particular past human society.
[src:oar/archaeological-culture] The connection between these types is an empirical observation.
[src:oar/archaeological-culture] Their interpretation in terms of ethnic or political groups is based on archaeologists' understanding.
[src:oar/archaeological-culture] However, this is often subject to long-unresolved debates.
[src:oar/archaeological-culture] The concept of the archaeological culture is fundamental to culture-historical archaeology.
[src:oar/archaeological-culture] Different cultural groups have material culture items that differ both functionally and aesthetically due to varying cultural and social practices.
[src:oar/archaeological-culture] This notion is observably true on the broadest scales.
[src:oar/archaeological-culture] For example, the equipment associated with the brewing of tea varies greatly across the world.
[src:oar/archaeological-culture] Social relations to material culture often include notions of identity and status.
[src:oar/archaeological-culture] Advocates of culture-historical archaeology use the notion to argue that sets of material culture can be used to trace ancient groups of people that were either self-identifying societies or ethnic groups.
[src:oar/archaeological-culture] Archaeological culture is a classifying device to order archaeological data, focused on artifacts as an expression of culture rather than people.
[src:oar/archaeological-culture] The concept of an archaeological culture was crucial to linking the typological analysis of archaeological evidence to mechanisms that attempted to explain why they change through time.
[src:oar/archaeological-culture] The key explanations favoured by culture-historians were the diffusion of forms from one group to another or the migration of the peoples themselves.
[src:oar/archaeological-culture] A simplistic example of the process might be that if one pottery-type had handles similar to those of a neighbouring type but decoration similar to a different neighbour, the idea for the two features might have diffused from the neighbours.
[src:oar/archaeological-culture] Conversely, if one pottery type suddenly replaces a great diversity of pottery types in an entire region, that might be interpreted as a new group migrating in with this new style.
[src:oar/archaeological-culture] This idea of culture is known as normative culture.
[src:oar/archaeological-culture] It relies on the assumption found in the view of archaeological culture that artifacts found are "an expression of cultural norms," and that these norms define culture.
[src:oar/archaeological-culture] This view is also required to be polythetic; multiple artifacts must be found for a site to be classified under a specific archaeological culture.
[src:oar/archaeological-culture] One trait alone does not result in a culture, a combination of traits is required.
[src:oar/archaeological-culture] This view culture gives life to the artifacts themselves.
[src:oar/archaeological-culture] Archaeological cultures were equated with separate 'peoples' (ethnic groups or races), leading in some cases to distinct nationalist archaeologies.
[src:oar/archaeological-culture] Most archaeological cultures are named after either the type of artifact or the type site that defines the culture.
[src:oar/archaeological-culture] For example, cultures may be named after pottery types such as Linear Pottery culture or Funnelbeaker culture.
[src:oar/archaeological-culture] More frequently, they are named after the site at which the culture was first defined, such as the Hallstatt culture or Clovis culture.
[src:oar/archaeological-culture] Since the term "culture" has multiple different meanings, scholars have also coined a more specific term, paleoculture, as a specific designation for prehistoric cultures.
[src:oar/archaeological-culture] The use of the term "culture" entered archaeology through 19th-century German ethnography, where the *Kultur* of tribal groups and rural peasants was distinguished from the *Zivilisation* of urbanised peoples.
[src:oar/archaeological-culture] In contrast to the broader use of the word that was introduced to English-language anthropology by Edward Burnett Tylor, *Kultur* was used by German ethnologists to describe the distinctive ways of life of a particular people or *Volk*, in this sense equivalent to the French *civilisation*.
[src:oar/archaeological-culture] Works of *Kulturgeschichte* (culture history) were produced by a number of German scholars, particularly Gustav Klemm, from 1780 onwards, reflecting a growing interest in ethnicity in 19th-century Europe.
[src:oar/archaeological-culture] The first use of "culture" in an archaeological context was in Christian Thomsen's 1836 work *Ledetraad til Nordisk Oldkyndighed* (Danish: *Guide to Northern Antiquity*).
[src:oar/archaeological-culture] It was not until the 20th century and the works of German prehistorian and fervent nationalist Gustaf Kossinna that the idea of archaeological cultures became central to the discipline.
[src:oar/archaeological-culture] Kossinna saw the archaeological record as a mosaic of clearly defined cultures (or *Kultur-Gruppen*, culture groups) that were strongly associated with race.
[src:oar/archaeological-culture] He was particularly interested in reconstructing the movements of what he saw as the direct prehistoric ancestors of Germans, Slavs, Celts and other major Indo-European ethnic groups in order to trace the Aryan race to its homeland or *Urheimat*.
[src:oar/archaeological-culture] The strongly racist character of Kossinna's work meant it had little direct influence outside of Germany at the time (the Nazi Party enthusiastically embraced his theories), or at all after World War II.
[src:oar/archaeological-culture] However, the more general "culture history" approach to archaeology that he began did replace social evolutionism as the dominant paradigm for much of the 20th century.
[src:oar/archaeological-culture] Kossinna's basic concept of the archaeological culture, stripped of its racial aspects, was adopted by Vere Gordon Childe and Franz Boas, at the time the most influential archaeologists in Britain and America respectively.
[src:oar/archaeological-culture] Childe, in particular, was responsible for formulating the definition of archaeological culture that still largely applies today.
[src:oar/archaeological-culture] He defined archaeological culture as artifacts and remains that consistently occur together.
[src:oar/archaeological-culture] This introduced a "new and discrete usage of the term which was significantly different from current anthropological usage." His definition, in particular, was purely a classifying device to order the archaeological data.
[src:oar/archaeological-culture] Later archaeologists have questioned the straightforward relationship between material culture and human societies.
[src:oar/archaeological-culture] The definition of archaeological cultures and their relationship to past people has become less clear; in some cases, what was believed to be a monolithic culture is shown by further study to be discrete societies.
[src:oar/archaeological-culture] For example, the Windmill Hill culture now serves as a general label for several different groups that occupied southern Great Britain during the Neolithic.
[src:oar/archaeological-culture] Conversely, some archaeologists have argued that some supposedly distinctive cultures are manifestations of a wider culture, but they show local differences based on environmental factors such as those related to Clactonian man.
[src:oar/archaeological-culture] Conversely, archaeologists may make a distinction between material cultures that actually belonged to a single cultural group.
[src:oar/archaeological-culture] It has been highlighted, for example, that village-dwelling and nomadic Bedouin Arabs have radically different material cultures even if in other respects, they are similar.
[src:oar/archaeological-culture] In the past, such synchronous findings were often interpreted as representing intrusion by other groups.
[src:oar/archaeological-culture] The concept of archaeological cultures is itself a divisive subject within the archaeological field.
[src:oar/archaeological-culture] When first developed, archaeological culture was viewed as a reflection of actual human culture.
[src:oar/archaeological-culture] — Matthew Johnson, *Archaeological Theory: An Introduction*, p.
[src:oar/archaeological-culture] Archaeological culture is presently useful for sorting and assembling artifacts, especially in European archaeology, which often falls towards culture-historical archaeology.
[src:oar/oar] An **oar** is an implement used for water-borne propulsion.
[src:oar/oar] The difference between oars and paddles is that oars are used exclusively for rowing.
[src:oar/oar] In rowing the oar is connected to the vessel by means of a pivot point for the oar, either an oarlock, or a thole pin.
[src:oar/oar] The oar is placed in the pivot point with a short portion inside the vessel, and a much larger portion outside.
[src:oar/oar] The rower pulls on the short end of the oar, while the long end is in the water.
[src:oar/oar] By contrast, paddles are held in both hands by the paddler, and are not attached to the vessel.
[src:oar/oar] Rowers generally face the stern of the vessel, reach towards the stern, and insert the blade of their oar in the water.
[src:oar/oar] As they lean back, towards the vessel's bow, the blade of their oars pivots in the oarlock, and the end in the water moves towards the stern, providing forward thrust.
[src:oar/oar] For thousands of years vessels were powered either by sails, or by the mechanical work of rowers, or by paddlers.
[src:oar/oar] It is common for an oar propelled vessel to also have the option to be powered by sail, both in antiquity (for instance the galley) and more recently.
[src:oar/oar] Rowing oars have been used since the early Neolithic period.
[src:oar/oar] Wooden oars, with canoe-shaped pottery, dating from 5000–4500 BC have been discovered in a Hemudu culture site at Yuyao, Zhejiang, in modern China.
[src:oar/oar] In 1999, an oar measuring 63.4 cm (2 ft) in length, dating from 4000 BC, was unearthed in Ishikawa Prefecture, Japan.
[src:oar/oar] Oars have traditionally been made of wood.
[src:oar/oar] The form is a long shaft (or loom) with a flat blade on the end.
[src:oar/oar] Where the oar connects to the boat there is a "collar" (or button), often made of leather, which stops the oar slipping past the rowlock.
[src:oar/oar] Oars usually have a handle about 150mm long, which may be a material sleeve or alternatively an ovoid shape carved to fit the hands.
[src:oar/oar] Which class of lever depends on the frame of reference.
[src:oar/oar] From the rower's perspective, the oar can be seen as a **Class I** lever.
[src:oar/oar] The oar is fixed in the oarlock, the rower pulls on the handle, and the blade moves in the opposite direction to propel the boat.
[src:oar/oar] The blade is further from the oarlock than the rower's hands.
[src:oar/oar] So, the heavy force of a short rowing motion becomes a smaller force over a greater distance.
[src:oar/oar] From an observer on the shore, the oar is instead a **Class II** lever.
[src:oar/oar] Here, the fulcrum is the *blade*, planted in the water.
[src:oar/oar] The rower pulls on the handle and the boat moves along with them.
[src:oar/oar] The "Class II" perspective is important to competitive rowing.
[src:oar/oar] Effective rowers learn to lever the boat past the end of the blade, rather than pulling the blade through the water.
[src:oar/oar] The World Rowing Federation rulebook defines oars as Class II.
[src:oar/oar] Both the Class I and Class II perspectives can be used to calculate the forces on the rower, boat, and water, with equivalent results.
[src:oar/oar] The calculations are simpler for the Class I perspective.
[src:oar/oar] The mechanical advantage of the oar depends on the length of the oar from the oarlock to the blade, compared to the length from the oarlock to the rower's hand(s).
[src:oar/oar] The further away from the oarlock the blade is, the more difficult it is to row and the more distance each stroke will move.
[src:oar/oar] This is a normal, usually wooden oar to which weight has been added at the inboard end so that the blade end is noticeably lighter and easier for a rower to operate without fatigue.
[src:oar/oar] For a 7-foot (2.1 m) oar the balance point is about 12 inches outboard of the rowlock.
[src:oar/oar] Often surplus wood is removed from the blade's width and thickness and at the neck between the blade and the shaft to further reduce outboard weight.
[src:oar/oar] As the rower is expending less energy accelerating the (now-reduced) mass of the oar back-and-forth, and will experience less fatigue constantly exerting downward force on the handle (vs. an unbalanced version) -- this type of oar is more efficient and thus preferable for long-range rowing.
[src:oar/oar] The oars used for transport come in a variety of sizes.
[src:oar/oar] The oars used in small dinghies or rafts can be less than 2 metres long.
[src:oar/oar] In classical times warships were propelled by very long oars that might have several oarsmen per oar.
[src:oar/oar] These oars could be more than a dozen metres long.
[src:oar/oar] According to Callixenus, as cited by Athenaeus, in the great ship of Ptolemy the oars of the upper tier were over 50 feet (15 m) in length with handles leaded so as to equalize the weight inboard and outboard.
[src:oar/oar] The oars used in competitive rowing are long (250–300 cm) poles with one flat end about 50 cm long and 25 cm wide, called the blade.
[src:oar/oar] The part of the oar the oarsman holds while rowing is called the handle.
[src:oar/oar] While rowing, the oars are supported by metal frames attached to the side of the boat called riggers, while the oar fits into the oarlocks at the ends of each rigger.
[src:oar/oar] Classic oars were made of wood, but modern oars are made from synthetic material, the most common being carbon fibre.
[src:oar/oar] The sport of competitive rowing has developed a tradition of using an oar as a memento of significant race wins.
[src:oar/oar] A 'trophy oar' is not presented at the end of the race as a more familiar precious metal cup might be, but rather given by the club, school or university that the winning crew or rower represented.
[src:oar/oar] A trophy oar is a competition oar that has been painted in the club colours and has then had the details of the race signwritten on the face of the blade.
[src:oar/oar] The most common format has the coat of arms or crest of the club or school positioned in the centre, with the crew names and the race details arranged around this.
[src:oar/oar] Many older universities (Oxford and Cambridge for example, as well as Yale and Harvard) and their colleges have long histories of using the trophy oar and many examples are on display in club houses around the world.
[src:oar/oar] In Norway, both Fedje Municipality and Herøy Municipality both have oars in their coat of arms.
[src:oar/oar] Oars have been used to describe various animals with characteristics that closely resemble the said rowing implement.
[src:oar/oar] The members of the Family Regalecidae, elongated deep-sea fishes, are called oarfish because their body shape is similar to that of an oar.
[src:oar/oar] The hawksbill turtle's genus of Eretmochelys is derived from the Greek root *eretmo*, which roughly translates to *oar*.
[src:oar/oar] The turtle was so-named because of the oar-like shape of its front flippers.
